# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chirgwin-coulson-weights
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The basis set can either be composed of atomic orbitals (yielding the linear combination of atomic orbitals approach), which is the usual choice within the quantum chemistry community; plane waves which are typically used within the solid state community, or real-space approaches.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Several types of atomic orbitals can be used: Gaussian-type orbitals, Slater-type orbitals, or numerical atomic orbitals.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Out of the three, Gaussian-type orbitals are by far the most often used, as they allow efficient implementations of post-Hartree–Fock methods.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] In modern computational chemistry, quantum chemical calculations are performed using a finite set of basis functions.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] When the finite basis is expanded towards an (infinite) complete set of functions, calculations using such a basis set are said to approach the complete basis set (CBS) limit.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] In this context, *basis function* and *atomic orbital* are sometimes used interchangeably, although the basis functions are usually not true atomic orbitals.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Within the basis set, the wavefunction is represented as a vector, the components of which correspond to coefficients of the basis functions in the linear expansion.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] In such a basis, one-electron operators correspond to matrices (a.k.a. rank two tensors), whereas two-electron operators are rank four tensors.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] When molecular calculations are performed, it is common to use a basis composed of atomic orbitals, centered at each nucleus within the molecule (linear combination of atomic orbitals ansatz).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The physically best motivated basis set are Slater-type orbitals (STOs), which are solutions to the Schrödinger equation of hydrogen-like atoms, and decay exponentially far away from the nucleus.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] It can be shown that the molecular orbitals of Hartree–Fock and density-functional theory also exhibit exponential decay.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Furthermore, S-type STOs also satisfy Kato's cusp condition at the nucleus, meaning that they are able to accurately describe electron density near the nucleus.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] However, hydrogen-like atoms lack many-electron interactions, thus the orbitals do not accurately describe electron state correlations.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Unfortunately, calculating integrals with STOs is computationally difficult and it was later realized by Frank Boys that STOs could be approximated as linear combinations of Gaussian-type orbitals (GTOs) instead.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Because the product of two GTOs can be written as a linear combination of GTOs, integrals with Gaussian basis functions can be written in closed form, which leads to huge computational savings (see John Pople).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Dozens of Gaussian-type orbital basis sets have been published in the literature.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Basis sets typically come in hierarchies of increasing size, giving a controlled way to obtain more accurate solutions, however at a higher cost.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The smallest basis sets are called *minimal basis sets*.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] A minimal basis set is one in which, on each atom in the molecule, a single basis function is used for each orbital in a Hartree–Fock calculation on the free atom.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] For atoms such as lithium, basis functions of p type are also added to the basis functions that correspond to the 1s and 2s orbitals of the free atom, because lithium also has a 1s2p bound state.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] For example, each atom in the second period of the periodic system (Li – Ne) would have a basis set of five functions (two s functions and three p functions).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] A minimal basis set may already be exact for the gas-phase atom at the self-consistent field level of theory.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] In the next level, additional functions are added to describe polarization of the electron density of the atom in molecules.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] These are called **polarization functions**.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] For example, while the minimal basis set for hydrogen is one function approximating the 1s atomic orbital, a simple polarized basis set typically has two s- and one p-function (which consists of three basis functions: px, py and pz).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] This adds flexibility to the basis set, effectively allowing molecular orbitals involving the hydrogen atom to be more asymmetric about the hydrogen nucleus.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] This is very important for modeling chemical bonding, because the bonds are often polarized.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Similarly, d-type functions can be added to a basis set with valence p orbitals, and f-functions to a basis set with d-type orbitals, and so on.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Another common addition to basis sets is the addition of **diffuse functions**.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] These are extended Gaussian basis functions with a small exponent, which give flexibility to the "tail" portion of the atomic orbitals, far away from the nucleus.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Diffuse basis functions are important for describing anions or dipole moments, but they can also be important for accurate modeling of intra- and inter-molecular bonding.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The most common minimal basis set is STO-nG, where n is an integer.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The STO-nG basis sets are derived from a minimal Slater-type orbital basis set, with *n* representing the number of Gaussian primitive functions used to represent each Slater-type orbital.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Minimal basis sets typically give rough results that are insufficient for research-quality publication, but are much cheaper than their larger counterparts.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] There are several other minimum basis sets that have been used such as the MidiX basis sets.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] During most molecular bonding, it is the valence electrons which principally take part in the bonding.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] In recognition of this fact, it is common to represent valence orbitals by more than one basis function (each of which can in turn be composed of a fixed linear combination of primitive Gaussian functions).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Basis sets in which there are multiple basis functions corresponding to each valence atomic orbital are called valence double, triple, quadruple-zeta, and so on, basis sets (zeta, ζ, was commonly used to represent the exponent of an STO basis function).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Since the different orbitals of the split have different spatial extents, the combination allows the electron density to adjust its spatial extent appropriate to the particular molecular environment.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] In contrast, minimal basis sets lack the flexibility to adjust to different molecular environments.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The notation for the *split-valence* basis sets arising from the group of John Pople is typically *X-YZg*.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] In this case, *X* represents the number of primitive Gaussians comprising each core atomic orbital basis function.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The *Y* and *Z* indicate that the valence orbitals are composed of two basis functions each, the first one composed of a linear combination of *Y* primitive Gaussian functions, the other composed of a linear combination of *Z* primitive Gaussian functions.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] In this case, the presence of two numbers after the hyphens implies that this basis set is a *split-valence double-zeta* basis set.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Split-valence triple- and quadruple-zeta basis sets are also used, denoted as *X-YZWg*, *X-YZWVg*, etc.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Polarization functions are denoted by two different notations.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The original Pople notation added "*" to indicate that all "heavy" atoms (everything but H and He) have a small set of polarization functions added to the basis (in the case of carbon, a set of 3d orbital functions).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The "**" notation indicates that all "light" atoms also receive polarization functions (this adds a set of 2p orbitals to the basis for each hydrogen atom).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Eventually it became desirable to add more polarization to the basis sets, and a new notation was developed in which the number and types of polarization functions are given explicitly in parentheses in the order (heavy,light) but with the principal quantum numbers of the orbitals implicit.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] For example, the * notation becomes (d) and the ** notation is now given as (d,p).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] If instead 3d and 4f functions were added to each heavy atom and 2p, 3p, 3d functions were added to each light atom, the notation would become (df,2pd).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] In all cases, diffuse functions are indicated by either adding a + before the letter G (diffuse functions on heavy atoms only) or ++ (diffuse functions are added to all atoms).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The Pople basis sets were originally developed for use in Hartree-Fock calculations.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Since then, correlation-consistent or polarization-consistent basis sets (see below) have been developed which are usually more appropriate for correlated wave function calculations.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Some of the most widely used basis sets are those developed by Dunning and coworkers, since they are designed for converging post-Hartree–Fock calculations systematically to the complete basis set limit using empirical extrapolation techniques.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] For first- and second-row atoms, the basis sets are cc-pVNZ where *N* = *D*,*T*,*Q*,5,6,...
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The 'cc-p', stands for 'correlation-consistent polarized' and the 'V' indicates that only basis sets for the valence orbitals are of multiple-zeta quality.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] (Like the Pople basis sets, the core orbitals are of single-zeta quality.) They include successively larger shells of polarization (correlating) functions (*d*, *f*, *g*, etc.).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] More recently these 'correlation-consistent polarized' basis sets have become widely used and are the current state of the art for correlated or post-Hartree–Fock calculations.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The *aug-* prefix is added if diffuse functions are included in the basis.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] For period-3 atoms (Al–Ar), additional functions have turned out to be necessary; these are the cc-pV(N+d)Z basis sets.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Even larger atoms may employ pseudopotential basis sets, cc-pVNZ-PP, or relativistic-contracted Douglas-Kroll basis sets, cc-pVNZ-DK.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] While the usual Dunning basis sets are for valence-only calculations, the sets can be augmented with further functions that describe core electron correlation.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] These core-valence sets (cc-pCVXZ) can be used to approach the exact solution to the all-electron problem, and they are necessary for accurate geometric and nuclear property calculations.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Weighted core-valence sets (cc-pwCVXZ) have also been recently suggested.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The weighted sets aim to capture core-valence correlation, while neglecting most of core-core correlation, in order to yield accurate geometries with smaller cost than the cc-pCVXZ sets.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Diffuse functions can also be added for describing anions and long-range interactions such as Van der Waals forces, or to perform electronic excited-state calculations, electric field property calculations.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] A recipe for constructing additional augmented functions exists; as many as five augmented functions have been used in second hyperpolarizability calculations in the literature.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Because of the rigorous construction of these basis sets, extrapolation can be done for almost any energetic property.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] However, care must be taken when extrapolating energy differences as the individual energy components converge at different rates: the Hartree–Fock energy converges exponentially, whereas the correlation energy converges only polynomially.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] To understand how to get the number of functions, consider the cc-pVDZ basis set for H: There are two *s* (*L* = 0) orbitals and one *p* (*L* = 1) orbital that has 3 angular-momentum components along the *z*-axis (*m*L = −1,0,1) corresponding to *p**x*, *p**y* and *p**z*.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Thus, there are five spatial orbitals in total.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Note that each orbital can hold two electrons of opposite spin.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] As another example, Ar [1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, 3p] has 3 s orbitals (*L* = 0) and 2 sets of p orbitals (*L* = 1).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Using cc-pVDZ, orbitals are [1s, 2s, 2p, 3s, 3s, 3p, 3p, 3d'] (where ' represents the added in polarisation orbitals), with 4 s orbitals (4 basis functions), 3 sets of p orbitals (3 × 3 = 9 basis functions), and 1 set of d orbitals (5 basis functions).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Adding up the basis functions gives a total of 18 functions for Ar with the cc-pVDZ basis-set.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Density-functional theory has recently become widely used in computational chemistry.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] However, the correlation-consistent basis sets described above are suboptimal for density-functional theory, because the correlation-consistent sets have been designed for post-Hartree–Fock, while density-functional theory exhibits much more rapid basis set convergence than wave function methods.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Adopting a similar methodology to the correlation-consistent series, Frank Jensen introduced polarization-consistent (pc-n) basis sets as a way to quickly converge density functional theory calculations to the complete basis set limit.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Like the Dunning sets, the pc-n sets can be combined with basis set extrapolation techniques to obtain CBS values.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The pc-n sets can be augmented with diffuse functions to obtain augpc-n sets.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Some of the various valence adaptations of Karlsruhe basis sets are briefly described below.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Gaussian-type orbital basis sets are typically optimized to reproduce the lowest possible energy for the systems used to train the basis set.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] However, the convergence of the energy does not imply convergence of other properties, such as nuclear magnetic shieldings, the dipole moment, or the electron momentum density, which probe different aspects of the electronic wave function.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Manninen and Vaara have proposed completeness-optimized basis sets, where the exponents are obtained by maximization of the one-electron completeness profile instead of minimization of the energy.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Completeness-optimized basis sets are a way to easily approach the complete basis set limit of any property at any level of theory, and the procedure is simple to automatize.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Completeness-optimized basis sets are tailored to a specific property.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] This way, the flexibility of the basis set can be focused on the computational demands of the chosen property, typically yielding much faster convergence to the complete basis set limit than is achievable with energy-optimized basis sets.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Here, only the two parameters $\alpha _{l}$ and $\beta _{l}$ must be optimized, significantly reducing the dimension of the search space or even avoiding the exponent optimization problem.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] In order to properly describe electronic delocalized states, a previously optimized standard basis set can be complemented with additional delocalized Gaussian functions with small exponent values, generated by the even-tempered scheme.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] This approach has also been employed to generate basis sets for other types of quantum particles rather than electrons, like quantum nuclei, negative muons or positrons.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] In addition to localized basis sets, plane-wave basis sets can also be used in quantum-chemical simulations.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Typically, the choice of the plane wave basis set is based on a cutoff energy.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The plane waves in the simulation cell that fit below the energy criterion are then included in the calculation.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] These basis sets are popular in calculations involving three-dimensional periodic boundary conditions.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The main advantage of a plane-wave basis is that it is guaranteed to converge in a *smooth, monotonic manner* to the target wavefunction.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] In contrast, when localized basis sets are used, monotonic convergence to the basis set limit may be difficult due to problems with over-completeness: in a large basis set, functions on different atoms start to look alike, and many eigenvalues of the overlap matrix approach zero.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] In addition, certain integrals and operations are much easier to program and carry out with plane-wave basis functions than with their localized counterparts.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] For example, the kinetic energy operator is diagonal in the reciprocal space.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Integrals over real-space operators can be efficiently carried out using fast Fourier transforms.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The properties of the Fourier Transform allow a vector representing the gradient of the total energy with respect to the plane-wave coefficients to be calculated with a computational effort that scales as NPW*ln(NPW) where NPW is the number of plane-waves.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] When this property is combined with separable pseudopotentials of the Kleinman-Bylander type and pre-conditioned conjugate gradient solution techniques, the dynamic simulation of periodic problems containing hundreds of atoms becomes possible.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] In practice, plane-wave basis sets are often used in combination with an 'effective core potential' or pseudopotential, so that the plane waves are only used to describe the valence charge density.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] This is because core electrons tend to be concentrated very close to the atomic nuclei, resulting in large wavefunction and density gradients near the nuclei which are not easily described by a plane-wave basis set unless a very high energy cutoff, and therefore small wavelength, is used.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] This combined method of a plane-wave basis set with a core pseudopotential is often abbreviated as a *PSPW* calculation.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Furthermore, as all functions in the basis are mutually orthogonal and are not associated with any particular atom, plane-wave basis sets do not exhibit basis-set superposition error.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] However, the plane-wave basis set is dependent on the size of the simulation cell, complicating cell size optimization.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Due to the assumption of periodic boundary conditions, plane-wave basis sets are less well suited to gas-phase calculations than localized basis sets.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Large regions of vacuum need to be added on all sides of the gas-phase molecule in order to avoid interactions with the molecule and its periodic copies.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] However, the plane waves use a similar accuracy to describe the vacuum region as the region where the molecule is, meaning that obtaining the truly noninteracting limit may be computationally costly.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] A combination of some of the properties of localized basis sets and plane-wave approaches is achieved by linearized augmented-plane-wave (LAPW) basis sets.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] These are based on a partitioning of space into nonoverlapping spheres around each atom and an interstitial region in between the spheres.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] An LAPW basis function is a plane wave in the interstitial region, which is augmented by numerical atomic functions in each sphere.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The numerical atomic functions hereby provide a linearized representation of wave functions for arbitrary energies around automatically determined energy parameters.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Similarly to plane-wave basis sets an LAPW basis set is mainly determined by a cutoff parameter for the plane-wave representation in the interstitial region.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] In the spheres the variational degrees of freedom can be extended by adding local orbitals to the basis set.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] This allows representations of wavefunctions beyond the linearized description.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The plane waves in the interstitial region imply three-dimensional periodic boundary conditions, though it is possible to introduce additional augmentation regions to reduce this to one or two dimensions, e.g., for the description of chain-like structures or thin films.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The atomic-like representation in the spheres allows to treat each atom with its potential singularity at the nucleus and to not rely on a pseudopotential approximation.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The disadvantage of LAPW basis sets is its complex definition, which comes with many parameters that have to be controlled either by the user or an automatic recipe.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Another consequence of the form of the basis set are complex mathematical expressions, e.g., for the calculation of a Hamiltonian matrix or atomic forces.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Real-space approaches offer powerful methods to solve electronic structure problems thanks to their controllable accuracy.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Real-space basis sets can be thought to arise from the theory of interpolation, as the central idea is to represent the (unknown) orbitals in terms of some set of interpolation functions.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Various methods have been proposed for constructing the solution in real space, including finite elements, basis splines, Lagrange sinc-functions, and wavelets.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Finite difference algorithms are also often included in this category, even though precisely speaking, they do not form a proper basis set and are not variational unlike e.g. finite element methods.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] A common feature of all real-space methods is that the accuracy of the numerical basis set is improvable, so that the complete basis set limit can be reached in a systematical manner.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] For example, in finite element methods (FEMs), the wave function is represented as a linear combination of a set of piecewise polynomials.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] Lagrange interpolating polynomials (LIPs) are a commonly used basis for FEM calculations.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The local interpolation error in LIP basis of order n is of the form $h^{n+1}\max f^{(n+1)}(\xi )$ .
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/basis-set-chemistry] The use of high-order LIPs has been shown to be highly beneficial for accuracy.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Benzene is a natural constituent of petroleum and is one of the elementary petrochemicals.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Because of the cyclic continuous pi bonds between the carbon atoms and satisfying the rules of aromaticity and Hückel's rule, benzene is classed as an aromatic hydrocarbon.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Benzene is a colorless and highly flammable liquid with a sweet smell, and is partially responsible for the aroma of gasoline.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] It is used primarily as a precursor to the manufacture of chemicals with more complex structures, such as ethylbenzene and cumene, of which billions of kilograms are produced annually.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Although benzene is a major industrial chemical, it finds limited use in consumer items because of its toxicity.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Its particular effects on human health, such as the long-term results of accidental exposure, have been reported on by news organizations such as *The New York Times*.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] For instance, a 2022 article stated that benzene contamination in the Boston metropolitan area created hazards in multiple places and may eventually cause some cases of leukemia.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The word "*benzene*" derives from "*gum benzoin*" (benzoin resin), an aromatic resin known since ancient times in Southeast Asia, and later to European pharmacists and perfumers in the 16th century via trade routes.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] An acidic material was derived from benzoin by sublimation, and named "flowers of benzoin", or benzoic acid.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The hydrocarbon derived from benzoic acid thus acquired the names *benzin*, *benzol*, and *benzene*.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Michael Faraday first isolated and identified benzene in 1825 from the oily residue derived from the production of illuminating gas, giving it the name *bicarburet of hydrogen*.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In 1833, Eilhard Mitscherlich produced it by distilling benzoic acid (from gum benzoin) and lime.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In 1836, the French chemist Auguste Laurent named the substance "phène"; this word has become the root of the English word "phenol", which is hydroxylated benzene, and "phenyl", the radical formed by abstraction of a hydrogen atom from benzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In 1845, Charles Blachford Mansfield, working under August Wilhelm von Hofmann, isolated benzene from coal tar.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Four years later, Mansfield began the first industrial-scale production of benzene, based on the coal-tar method.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Gradually, the sense developed among chemists that a number of substances were chemically related to benzene, comprising a diverse chemical family.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In 1855, Hofmann was the first to apply the word "aromatic" to designate this family relationship, after a characteristic property of many of its members.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In 1997, benzene was detected in deep space.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The empirical formula for benzene was long known, but its highly polyunsaturated structure, with just one hydrogen atom for each carbon atom, was challenging to determine.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] But many chemists had begun to work on aromatic substances, especially in Germany, and relevant data was coming fast.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In 1865, the German chemist Friedrich August Kekulé published a paper in French (for he was then teaching in Francophone Belgium) suggesting that the structure contained a ring of six carbon atoms with alternating single and double bonds.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The next year he published a much longer paper in German on the same subject.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Kekulé's symmetrical ring could explain these curious facts, as well as benzene's 1:1 carbon-hydrogen ratio.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The new understanding of benzene, and hence of all aromatic compounds, proved to be so important for both pure and applied chemistry that in 1890 the German Chemical Society organized an elaborate appreciation in Kekulé's honor, celebrating the twenty-fifth anniversary of his first benzene paper.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Here Kekulé spoke of the creation of the theory.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] He said that he had discovered the ring shape of the benzene molecule after having a reverie or day-dream of a snake biting its own tail (a symbol in ancient cultures known as the ouroboros).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] This vision, he said, came to him after years of studying the nature of carbon-carbon bonds.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] This was seven years after he had solved the problem of how carbon atoms could bond to up to four other atoms at the same time.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Some historians have suggested that the parody was a lampoon of the snake anecdote, possibly already well known through oral transmission even if it had not yet appeared in print.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Kekulé's 1890 speech in which this anecdote appeared has been translated into English.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] If the anecdote is the memory of a real event, circumstances mentioned in the story suggest that it must have happened early in 1862.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In 1929, the cyclic nature of benzene was finally confirmed by the crystallographer Kathleen Lonsdale using X-ray diffraction methods.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Using large crystals of hexamethylbenzene, a benzene derivative with the same core of six carbon atoms, Lonsdale obtained diffraction patterns.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Through calculating more than thirty parameters, Lonsdale demonstrated that the benzene ring could not be anything but a flat hexagon, and provided accurate distances for all carbon-carbon bonds in the molecule.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The German chemist Wilhelm Körner suggested the prefixes ortho-, meta-, para- to distinguish di-substituted benzene derivatives in 1867; however, he did not use the prefixes to distinguish the relative positions of the substituents on a benzene ring.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] It was the German chemist Carl Gräbe who, in 1869, first used the prefixes ortho-, meta-, para- to denote specific relative locations of the substituents on a di-substituted aromatic ring (viz, naphthalene).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In 1870, the German chemist Viktor Meyer first applied Gräbe's nomenclature to benzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In 1903, Ludwig Roselius popularized the use of benzene to decaffeinate coffee.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] This discovery led to the production of Sanka.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Benzene was historically used as a significant component in many consumer products such as liquid wrench, several paint strippers, rubber cements, spot removers, and other products.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Manufacture of some of these benzene-containing formulations ceased in about 1950, although Liquid Wrench continued to contain significant amounts of benzene until the late 1970s.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Trace amounts of benzene are found in petroleum and coal.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] It is a byproduct of the incomplete combustion of many materials.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] For commercial use, until World War II, much of benzene was obtained as a by-product of coke production (or "coke-oven light oil") for the steel industry.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] However, in the 1950s, increased demand for benzene, especially from the growing polymers industry, necessitated the production of benzene from petroleum.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Today, most benzene comes from the petrochemical industry, with only a small fraction being produced from coal.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] X-ray diffraction reveals that benzene is a planar molecule with six-fold rotational symmetry, which is in the symmetry group, $D_{6h}$ .
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The carbon-carbon bond lengths of benzene are 140 picometers (pm) long, which are greater than a C=C double bond (135 pm) but shorter than a C-C single bond (147 pm).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In terms of bonding, the molecular orbital (MO) description involves three bonding pi-MOs.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] A valence bond description involves a superposition of resonance structures.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Its considerable stability and distinctive chemical properties a manifested in the phenomenon of aromaticity.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] To reflect the delocalized nature of the bonding, benzene is often depicted with a circle inside a hexagonal arrangement of carbon atoms.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Many important chemical compounds are derived from benzene by replacing one or more of its hydrogen atoms with another functional group.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Examples of simple benzene derivatives are phenol, toluene, and aniline, abbreviated PhOH, PhMe, and PhNH2, respectively.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Linking benzene rings gives biphenyl, C6H5–C6H5.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Further loss of hydrogen gives "fused" aromatic hydrocarbons, such as naphthalene, anthracene, phenanthrene, and pyrene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The limit of the fusion process is the hydrogen-free allotrope of carbon, graphite.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In heterocycles, carbon atoms in the benzene ring are replaced with other elements.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The most important variations contain nitrogen.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Replacing one CH with N gives the compound pyridine, C5H5N.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Although benzene and pyridine are *structurally* related, benzene cannot be converted into pyridine.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Replacement of a second CH bond with N gives, depending on the location of the second N, pyridazine, pyrimidine, or pyrazine.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Four chemical processes contribute to industrial benzene production: catalytic reforming, toluene hydrodealkylation, toluene disproportionation, and steam cracking etc.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] According to the ATSDR Toxicological Profile for benzene, between 1978 and 1981, catalytic reformates accounted for approximately 44–50% of the total US benzene production.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In catalytic reforming, a mixture of hydrocarbons with boiling points between 60 and 200 °C is blended with hydrogen gas and then exposed to a bifunctional platinum chloride or rhenium chloride catalyst at 500–525 °C and pressures ranging from 8–50 atm.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Under these conditions, aliphatic hydrocarbons form rings and lose hydrogen to become aromatic hydrocarbons.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The aromatic products of the reaction are then separated from the reaction mixture (or reformate) by extraction with any one of a number of solvents, including diethylene glycol or sulfolane, and benzene is then separated from the other aromatics by distillation.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The extraction step of aromatics from the reformate is designed to produce aromatics with lowest non-aromatic components.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Recovery of the aromatics, commonly referred to as BTX (benzene, toluene and xylene isomers), involves such extraction and distillation steps.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In similar fashion to this catalytic reforming, UOP and BP commercialized a method from LPG (mainly propane and butane) to aromatics.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Toluene hydrodealkylation converts toluene to benzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In this hydrogen-intensive process, toluene is mixed with hydrogen, then passed over a chromium, molybdenum, or platinum oxide catalyst at 500–650 °C and 20–60 atm pressure.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Sometimes, higher temperatures are used instead of a catalyst (at the similar reaction condition).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] If the raw material stream contains much non-aromatic components (paraffins or naphthenes), those are likely decomposed to lower hydrocarbons such as methane, which increases the consumption of hydrogen.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Sometimes, xylenes and heavier aromatics are used in place of toluene, with similar efficiency.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] This is often called "on-purpose" methodology to produce benzene, compared to conventional BTX (benzene-toluene-xylene) extraction processes.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Toluene disproportionation (**TDP**) is the conversion of toluene to benzene and xylene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Given that demand for *para*-xylene (*p*-xylene) substantially exceeds demand for other xylene isomers, a refinement of the TDP process called **Selective TDP** (STDP) may be used.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In this process, the xylene stream exiting the TDP unit is approximately 90% *p*-xylene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In some systems, even the benzene-to-xylenes ratio is modified to favor xylenes.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Steam cracking is the process for producing ethylene and other alkenes from aliphatic hydrocarbons.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Depending on the feedstock used to produce the olefins, steam cracking can produce a benzene-rich liquid by-product called *pyrolysis gasoline*.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Pyrolysis gasoline can be blended with other hydrocarbons as a gasoline additive, or routed through an extraction process to recover BTX aromatics (benzene, toluene and xylenes).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Although of no commercial significance, many other routes to benzene exist.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Phenol and halobenzenes can be reduced with metals.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Benzoic acid and its salts undergo decarboxylation to benzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The reaction of the diazonium compound derived from aniline with hypophosphorus acid gives benzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Alkyne trimerisation of acetylene gives benzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Complete decarboxylation of mellitic acid gives benzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Benzene is used mainly as an intermediate to make other chemicals, above all ethylbenzene (and other alkylbenzenes), cumene, cyclohexane, and nitrobenzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In 1988, it was reported that two-thirds of all chemicals on the American Chemical Society's lists contained at least one benzene ring.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] More than half of the entire benzene production is processed into ethylbenzene, a precursor to styrene, which is used to make polymers and plastics like polystyrene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Some 20% of the benzene production is used to manufacture cumene, which is needed to produce phenol and acetone for resins and adhesives.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Cyclohexane consumes around 10% of the world's benzene production; it is primarily used in the manufacture of nylon fibers, which are processed into textiles and engineering plastics.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Smaller amounts of benzene are used to make some types of rubbers, lubricants, dyes, detergents, drugs, explosives, and pesticides.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In 2013, the biggest consumer country of benzene was China, followed by the USA.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Benzene production is currently expanding in the Middle East and in Africa, whereas production capacities in Western Europe and North America are stagnating.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Toluene is now often used as a substitute for benzene, for instance as a fuel additive.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The solvent-properties of the two are similar, but toluene is less toxic and has a wider liquid range.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] As a gasoline (petrol) additive, benzene increases the octane rating and reduces knocking.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] As a consequence, gasoline often contained several percent benzene before the 1950s, when tetraethyl lead replaced it as the most widely used antiknock additive.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] With the global phaseout of leaded gasoline in the 1970s–1990s, benzene reappeared as a gasoline additive, although strictly limited in most nations.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] For example, in the United States, concern over its negative health effects and the possibility of benzene entering the groundwater has led to stringent regulation of gasoline's benzene content, with limits typically around 1%.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] European petrol specifications now contain the same 1% limit on benzene content.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The United States Environmental Protection Agency introduced new regulations in 2011 that lowered the benzene content in gasoline to 0.62%.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In some European languages, the word for petroleum or gasoline is an exact cognate of "benzene".
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] For instance all Germanic languages and Scandinavian languages refer to gasoline as 'bensin' or 'benzin'.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In Turkish and many Turkic languages the word of 'benzin' is used to refer the gasoline.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In Catalan and Italian the word 'benzina' can be used for gasoline.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In both Polish and Greek the word 'benzyna' is also used to mean gasoline or petrol.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The most common reactions of benzene involve substitution of a proton by other groups.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Electrophilic aromatic substitution is a general method of derivatizing benzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Benzene is sufficiently nucleophilic that it undergoes substitution by acylium ions and alkyl carbocations to give substituted derivatives.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The most widely practiced example of this reaction is the ethylation of benzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Approximately 24,700,000 tons of ethylbenzene were produced in 1999.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Highly instructive but of far less industrial significance is the Friedel-Crafts alkylation of benzene (and many other aromatic rings) using an alkyl halide in the presence of a strong Lewis acid catalyst.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Similarly, the Friedel-Crafts acylation is a related example of electrophilic aromatic substitution.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The reaction involves the acylation of benzene (or many other aromatic rings) with an acyl chloride using a strong Lewis acid catalyst such as aluminium chloride or Iron(III) chloride.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Using electrophilic aromatic substitution, many functional groups are introduced onto the benzene framework.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Sulfonation of benzene involves the use of oleum, a mixture of sulfuric acid with sulfur trioxide.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Sulfonated benzene derivatives are useful detergents.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In nitration, benzene reacts with nitronium ions (NO2+), which is a strong electrophile produced by combining sulfuric and nitric acids.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Nitrobenzene is the precursor to aniline.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Chlorination is achieved with chlorine to produce chlorobenzene in the presence of a Lewis acid catalyst such as aluminium chloride.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Hydrogenation is achieved by introducing hydrogen to the unsaturated compounds under high pressure in the presence of heterogeneous catalysts, such as finely divided nickel.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] This reaction converts benzene into cyclohexane.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Benzene derivatives are also converted into their respective saturated equivalents.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Whereas alkenes can be hydrogenated near room temperatures, benzene and its derivatives are more reluctant substrates, requiring temperatures exceeding 100 °C for hydrogenation to occur.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] This reaction is practiced on an industrial scale.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Typically, benzene is fully saturated into cyclohexane during hydrogenation.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] However, with the right conditions, benzene can be partially-hydrogenated to give cyclohexene or cyclohexadienes.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] A similar reaction is the Birch reduction, which is a non-catalytic process that converts benzene into cyclohexadiene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Benzene is an excellent ligand in the organometallic chemistry of low-valent metals.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Complexes containing benzene include the sandwich complex Cr(C6H6)2 as well as the half-sandwich complex [RuCl2(C6H6)]2.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Benzene is classified as a carcinogen, which increases the risk of cancer and other illnesses, and is also a notorious cause of bone marrow failure.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Substantial quantities of epidemiologic, clinical, and laboratory data link benzene to aplastic anemia, acute leukemia, bone marrow abnormalities and cardiovascular disease.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The specific hematologic malignancies that benzene is associated with include: acute myeloid leukemia (AML), aplastic anemia, myelodysplastic syndrome (MDS), acute lymphoblastic leukemia (ALL), and chronic myeloid leukemia (CML).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Carcinogenic activity of benzene was discovered by Swedish pharmacologist C.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Santesson in 1897 on female workers of a tire-making factory.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The American Petroleum Institute (API) stated in 1948 that "it is generally considered that the only absolutely safe concentration for benzene is zero".
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] There is no safe exposure level; even tiny amounts can cause harm.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The US Department of Health and Human Services (DHHS) classifies benzene as a human carcinogen.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Long-term exposure to excessive levels of benzene in the air causes leukemia, a potentially fatal cancer of the blood-forming organs.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In particular, acute myeloid leukemia or acute nonlymphocytic leukemia (AML & ANLL) is caused by benzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] IARC rated benzene as "known to be carcinogenic to humans" (Group 1).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] As benzene is ubiquitous in gasoline and hydrocarbon fuels that are in use everywhere, human exposure to benzene is a global health problem.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Benzene targets the liver, kidney, lung, heart and brain and can cause DNA strand breaks and chromosomal damage, therefore it is mutagenic.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Benzene causes cancer in animals including humans.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Benzene has been shown to cause cancer in both sexes of multiple species of laboratory animals exposed via various routes.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The major sources of benzene exposure are tobacco smoke, automobile service stations, exhaust from motor vehicles, and industrial emissions; however, ingestion and dermal absorption of benzene can also occur through contact with contaminated water.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Benzene is hepatically metabolized and excreted in the urine.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Measurement of air and water levels of benzene is accomplished through collection via activated charcoal tubes, which are then analyzed with a gas chromatograph.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The measurement of benzene in humans can be accomplished via urine, blood, and breath tests; however, all of these have their limitations because benzene is rapidly metabolized in the human body.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Exposure to benzene may lead progressively to aplastic anemia, leukaemia, and multiple myeloma.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) regulates levels of benzene in the workplace.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The maximum allowable amount of benzene in workroom air during an 8-hour workday, 40-hour workweek is 1 ppm.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] As benzene can cause cancer, National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) recommends that all workers wear special breathing equipment when they are likely to be exposed to benzene at levels exceeding the recommended (8-hour) exposure limit of 0.1 ppm.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The United States Environmental Protection Agency has set a maximum contaminant level for benzene in drinking water at 0.005 mg/L (5 ppb), as promulgated via the US National Primary Drinking Water Regulations.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] This regulation is based on preventing benzene leukemogenesis.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The maximum contaminant level goal (MCLG), a nonenforceable health goal that would allow an adequate margin of safety for the prevention of adverse effects, is zero benzene concentration in drinking water.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The EPA requires that spills or accidental releases into the environment of 10 pounds (4.5 kg) or more of benzene be reported.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The US Occupational Safety and Health Administration (OSHA) has set a permissible exposure limit of 1 part of benzene per million parts of air (1 ppm) in the workplace during an 8-hour workday, 40-hour workweek.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The short term exposure limit for airborne benzene is 5 ppm for 15 minutes.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] These legal limits were based on studies demonstrating compelling evidence of health risk to workers exposed to benzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The risk from exposure to 1 ppm for a working lifetime has been estimated as 5 excess leukemia deaths per 1,000 employees exposed.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] (This estimate assumes no threshold for benzene's carcinogenic effects.) OSHA has also established an action level of 0.5 ppm to encourage even lower exposures in the workplace.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The US National Institute for Occupational Safety and Health (NIOSH) revised the Immediately Dangerous to Life and Health (IDLH) concentration for benzene to 500 ppm.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In September 1995, NIOSH issued a new policy for developing recommended exposure limits (RELs) for substances, including carcinogens.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] As benzene can cause cancer, NIOSH recommends that all workers wear special breathing equipment when they are likely to be exposed to benzene at levels exceeding the REL (10-hour) of 0.1 ppm.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The NIOSH short-term exposure limit (STEL – 15 min) is 1 ppm.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] American Conference of Governmental Industrial Hygienists (ACGIH) adopted Threshold Limit Values (TLVs) for benzene at 0.02 ppm TWA in 2024.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Germany’s regulation comes through something called Technische Regeln für Gefahrstoffe which means Germany’s Technical Rule For Hazardous Substances.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The workspace exposure limit in Germany is TRGS 900.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Whereas the TRGS 910 sets the level of risk for the chemicals that can cause cancer and explains the amount that should be reduced.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] When it comes to the EU exposure limit it’s about 0.66 mg^3.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] When looking at TRGS 910 according to the numbers from national assessment criteria the target concentration is AC: 0.2 mg/m3 and the temporary upper concentration level is TC: 1.9 mg/m3.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Scientific research shows that there is correlation between leukemia and benzene exposure; average exposure to benzene below 5μg/m^3 lowered the leukemia burden from benzene by nearly a third.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] This information from the VegAS project shows how trying to control the level of benzene has a lot of importance since it has caused problems in the country.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] This project was funded by The Federal Ministry of Environment, Nature Conservation.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In terms of the benzene market, Germany is a top 3 producer in the European Union.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] It is the BASF that has responsibility when it comes to looking over chemicals such as benzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Also, Germany is in the top 6 when it comes to the exports in the world for benzene, same when it comes to imports.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] They are the 7th largest importers in the world as well.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] When looking at the EU, they are one of the largest traders when it comes to benzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Several tests can determine exposure to benzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Benzene itself can be measured in breath, blood, or urine, however such testing is usually limited to the first 24 hours post-exposure due to the relatively rapid removal of the chemical by exhalation or biotransformation.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The majority of people in developed countries have measureable baseline levels of benzene and other aromatic petroleum hydrocarbons in their blood.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In the body, benzene is enzymatically converted to a series of oxidation products including muconic acid, phenylmercapturic acid, phenol, catechol, hydroquinone and 1,2,4-trihydroxybenzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Most of these metabolites have some value as biomarkers of human exposure, since they accumulate in the urine in proportion to the extent and duration of exposure, and they may still be present for some days after exposure has ceased.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The current ACGIH biological exposure limits for occupational exposure are 500 μg/g creatinine for muconic acid and 25 μg/g creatinine for phenylmercapturic acid in an end-of-shift urine specimen.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Even if it is not a common substrate for metabolism, benzene can be oxidized by both bacteria and eukaryotes.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In bacteria, dioxygenase enzyme can add an oxygen to the ring, and the unstable product is immediately reduced (by NADH) to a cyclic diol with two double bonds, breaking the aromaticity.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Next, the diol is newly reduced by NADH to catechol.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The catechol is then metabolized to acetyl CoA and succinyl CoA, used by organisms mainly in the citric acid cycle for energy production.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Human metabolism of benzene is complex and begins in the liver.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] These include cytochrome P450 2E1 (CYP2E1), quinine oxidoreductase (NQ01 or DT-diaphorase or NAD(P)H dehydrogenase (quinone 1)), GSH, and myeloperoxidase (MPO).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] CYP2E1 is involved at multiple steps: converting benzene to oxepin (benzene oxide), phenol to hydroquinone, and hydroquinone to both benzenetriol and catechol.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Hydroquinone, benzenetriol and catechol are converted to polyphenols.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In the bone marrow, MPO converts these polyphenols to benzoquinones.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] NQ01 and GSH shift metabolism away from toxicity.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] NQ01 metabolizes benzoquinone toward polyphenols (counteracting the effect of MPO).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] GSH is involved with the formation of phenylmercapturic acid.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Genetic polymorphisms in these enzymes may induce loss of function or gain of function.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] For example, mutations in CYP2E1 increase activity and result in increased generation of toxic metabolites.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] NQ01 mutations result in loss of function and may result in decreased detoxification.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Myeloperoxidase mutations result in loss of function and may result in decreased generation of toxic metabolites.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] GSH mutations or deletions result in loss of function and result in decreased detoxification.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] These genes may be targets for genetic screening for susceptibility to benzene toxicity.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The paradigm of toxicological assessment of benzene is shifting towards the domain of molecular toxicology as it allows understanding of fundamental biological mechanisms in a better way.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Glutathione seems to play an important role by protecting against benzene-induced DNA breaks and it is being identified as a new biomarker for exposure and effect.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Benzene causes chromosomal aberrations in the peripheral blood leukocytes and bone marrow explaining the higher incidence of leukemia and multiple myeloma caused by chronic exposure.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] These aberrations can be monitored using fluorescent in situ hybridization (FISH) with DNA probes to assess the effects of benzene along with the hematological tests as markers of hematotoxicity.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Benzene metabolism involves enzymes coded for by polymorphic genes.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Studies have shown that genotype at these loci may influence susceptibility to the toxic effects of benzene exposure.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Individuals carrying variant of NAD(P)H:quinone oxidoreductase 1 (NQO1), microsomal epoxide hydrolase (EPHX) and deletion of the glutathione S-transferase T1 (GSTT1) showed a greater frequency of DNA single-stranded breaks.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] One way of understanding the carcinogenic effects of benzene is by examining the products of biological oxidation.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Pure benzene, for example, oxidizes in the body to produce an epoxide, benzene oxide, which is not excreted readily and can interact with DNA to produce harmful mutations.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Outdoor air may contain low levels of benzene from automobile service stations, wood smoke, tobacco smoke, the transfer of gasoline, exhaust from motor vehicles, and industrial emissions.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] About 50% of the entire nationwide (United States) exposure to benzene results from smoking tobacco or from exposure to tobacco smoke.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] After smoking 32 cigarettes per day, the smoker would take in about 1.8 mg of benzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] This amount is about 10 times the average daily intake of benzene by nonsmokers.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Inhaled benzene is primarily expelled unchanged through exhalation.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In a human study 16.4 to 41.6% of retained benzene was eliminated through the lungs within five to seven hours after a two- to three-hour exposure to 47 to 110 ppm and only 0.07 to 0.2% of the remaining benzene was excreted unchanged in the urine.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] After exposure to 63 to 405 mg/m3 of benzene for 1 to 5 hours, 51 to 87% was excreted in the urine as phenol over a period of 23 to 50 hours.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In another human study, 30% of absorbed dermally applied benzene, which is primarily metabolized in the liver, was excreted as phenol in the urine.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Under specific conditions and in the presence of other chemicals benzoic acid (a preservative) and ascorbic acid (Vitamin C) may interact to produce benzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In March 2006, the official Food Standards Agency in United Kingdom conducted a survey of 150 brands of soft drinks.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] It found that four contained benzene levels above World Health Organization limits.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] The affected batches were removed from sale.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Similar problems were reported by the US Food & Drug Administration.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] In 2005, the water supply to the city of Harbin in China with a population of almost nine million people, was cut off because of a major benzene exposure.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Benzene leaked into the Songhua River, which supplies drinking water to the city, after an explosion at a China National Petroleum Corporation (CNPC) factory in the city of Jilin on 13 November 2005.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] When plastic water pipes are subject to high heat, the water may be contaminated with benzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/benzene] Nazi Germany used benzene administered via injection as one of their many methods for killing.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] The compound was reported in 1926 by the chemists Alfred Stock and Erich Pohland by a reaction of diborane with ammonia.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] Borazine can be synthesized by treating diborane and ammonia in a 1:2 ratio at 250–300 °C with a conversion of 50%.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] Borazine is isoelectronic with benzene and has similar connectivity, so it is sometimes referred to as "inorganic benzene".
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] This comparison is not rigorously valid due to the electronegativity difference between boron and nitrogen.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] X-ray crystallographic structural determinations show that the bond lengths within the borazine ring are all equivalent at 1.429 Å, a property shared by benzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] However, the borazine ring does not form a perfect hexagon.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] The bond angle is 117.1° at the boron atoms and 122.9° at the nitrogens, giving the molecule the *D*3*h* symmetry point group.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] The electronegativity of boron (2.04 on the Pauling scale) compared to that of nitrogen (3.04) and also the electron deficiency on the boron atom and the lone pair on nitrogen favor alternative mesomer structures for borazine.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] Boron behaves as a Lewis acid and nitrogen behaves as a Lewis base.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] Due to its similarities to benzene, there have been a number of computational and experimental analyses of borazine's aromaticity.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] The number of pi electrons in borazine obeys the 4n + 2 rule, and the B-N bond lengths are equal, which suggests the compound may be aromatic.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] The electronegativity difference between boron and nitrogen, however, creates an unequal sharing of charge which results in bonds with greater ionic character, and thus it is expected to have poorer delocalization of electrons than the all-carbon analog.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] Borazine, with a standard enthalpy change of formation Δf*H* of −531 kJ/mol, is thermally very stable.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] Natural bond orbital (NBO) analysis suggests weak aromaticity in borazine.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] In the NBO model, B-N bonds in the ring are slightly displaced from the nuclear axes, and B and N have large differences in charge.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] Natural chemical shielding (NCS) analysis provides some further evidence for aromaticity based on a contribution of the B-N π bond to magnetic shielding.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] Computations based on NBO orbitals show that this π bond allows for weak ring current which somewhat counteracts a magnetic field simulated at the center of the borazine ring.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] A small ring current does suggest some delocalization.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] Topological analysis of bonding in borazine by the electron localization function (ELF) indicates that borazine can be described as a π aromatic compound.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] However, the bonding in borazine is less delocalized than in benzene based on a difference in bifurcation values of the electron basins.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] Larger bifurcation values indicate better electron delocalization, and it is argued that when this bifurcation value is greater than 0.70, the delocalization is sufficient to designate a compound aromatic.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] For benzene, this value is 0.91, but the borazine π system bifurcates at the ELF value 0.682.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] This is caused by the difference in electronegativity between B and N, which produces a weaker bond interaction than the C-C interaction in benzene, leading to increased localization of electrons on the B-H and N-H units.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] The bifurcation value is slightly below the limit of 0.70 which suggests moderate aromaticity.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] Borazine hydrolyzes readily, yielding boric acid, ammonia, and hydrogen.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] With hydrogen chloride it forms an adduct.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] The addition reaction with bromine does not require a catalyst.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] Borazines undergo nucleophilic attack at boron and electrophilic attack at nitrogen.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] Boron nitride can be prepared by heating polyborazylene to 1000 °C.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] Borazines are also starting materials for other potential ceramics such as boron carbonitrides.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] Borazine can also be used as a precursor to grow hexagonal boron nitride (h-BN) thin films and single layers on catalytic surfaces such as copper, platinum, nickel iron and many more, with chemical vapor deposition (CVD).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] Polyborazylene has been proposed as a recycled hydrogen storage medium for hydrogen fuel cell vehicle applications, using a "single pot" process for digestion and reduction to recreate ammonia borane.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] Among other B-N type compounds mixed amino-nitro substituted borazines have been predicted to outperform carbon based explosives such as CL-20.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] Carborazine (C 2H 2B 2N 2) is a six-membered aromatic ring with two carbon atoms, two nitrogen atoms, and two boron atoms in opposing pairs.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/borazine] 1,2-Dihydro-1,2-azaborine (C 4BNH 6) is a six-membered ring with four carbon atoms, one nitrogen atom, and one boron atom.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Butadiene undergoes chemical degradation in the atmosphere, but it can nevertheless be found in low levels in the air of urban and suburban areas due to emission by motor vehicles.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] The name butadiene can also refer to the isomer, 1,2-butadiene, which is a cumulated diene with structure H2C=C=CH−CH3.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] This allene has no industrial significance.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Caventou isolated butadiene from the pyrolysis of amyl alcohol.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] This hydrocarbon was identified as butadiene in 1886, after Henry Edward Armstrong isolated it from among the pyrolysis products of petroleum.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] In 1910, the Russian chemist Sergei Lebedev polymerized butadiene and obtained a material with rubber-like properties.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] This polymer was, however, found to be too soft to replace natural rubber in many applications, notably automobile tires.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] The butadiene industry originated in the years before World War II.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Many of the belligerent nations realized that in the event of war, they could be cut off from rubber plantations controlled by the British Empire, and sought to reduce their dependence on natural rubber.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] In 1929, Eduard Tschunker and Walter Bock, working for IG Farben in Germany, made a copolymer of styrene and butadiene that could be used in automobile tires.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Worldwide production quickly ensued, with butadiene being produced from grain alcohol in the Soviet Union and the United States, and from coal-derived acetylene in Germany.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] In 2020, 14.2 million tons were estimated to have been produced.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] In the United States, western Europe, and Japan, butadiene is produced as a byproduct of the steam cracking process used to produce ethylene and other alkenes.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] When mixed with steam and briefly heated to very high temperatures (often over 900 °C), aliphatic hydrocarbons give up hydrogen to produce a complex mixture of unsaturated hydrocarbons, including butadiene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] The quantity of butadiene produced depends on the hydrocarbons used as feed.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Light feeds, such as ethane, give primarily ethylene when cracked, but heavier feeds favor the formation of heavier olefins, butadiene, and aromatic hydrocarbons.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Butadiene is typically isolated from the other four-carbon hydrocarbons produced in steam cracking by extractive distillation using a polar aprotic solvent such as acetonitrile, *N*-methyl-2-pyrrolidone, furfural, or dimethylformamide, from which it is then stripped by distillation.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Butadiene can also be produced by the catalytic dehydrogenation of normal butane (*n*-butane).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] The first such post-war commercial plant, producing 65,000 tons per year of butadiene, began operations in 1957 in Houston, Texas.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Prior to that, in the 1940s the Rubber Reserve Company, a part of the United States government, constructed several plants in Borger, Texas, Toledo, Ohio, and El Segundo, California, to produce synthetic rubber for the war effort as part of the United States Synthetic Rubber Program.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Total capacity was 68 KMTA (Kilo Metric Tons per Annum).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Today, butadiene from *n*-butane is commercially produced using the Houdry Catadiene process, which was developed during World War II.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] This entails treating butane over alumina and chromia at high temperatures.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] In other parts of the world, including South America, Eastern Europe, China, and India, butadiene is also produced from ethanol.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] While not competitive with steam cracking for producing large volumes of butadiene, lower capital costs make production from ethanol a viable option for smaller-capacity plants.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] This process was the basis for the Soviet Union's synthetic rubber industry during and after World War II, and it remained in limited use in Russia and other parts of eastern Europe until the end of the 1970s.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] At the same time this type of manufacture was canceled in Brazil.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] As of 2017, no butadiene was produced industrially from ethanol.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] This process was one of the three used in the United States to produce "government rubber" during World War II, although it is less economical than the butane or butene routes for the large volumes.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Still, three plants with a total capacity of 200,000 tons per year were constructed in the U.S.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] (Institute, West Virginia, Louisville, Kentucky, and Kobuta, Pennsylvania) with start-ups completed in 1943, the Louisville plant initially created butadiene from acetylene generated by an associated calcium carbide plant.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] The process remains in use today in China and India.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] 1,3-Butadiene can also be produced by catalytic dehydrogenation of normal butenes.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Synthetic Rubber Program (USSRP) during World War II.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] The process was much more economical than the alcohol or n-butane route but competed with aviation gasoline for available butene molecules (butenes were plentiful thanks to catalytic cracking).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] The USSRP constructed several plants in Baton Rouge and Lake Charles, Louisiana; Houston, Baytown, and Port Neches, Texas; and Torrance, California.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] In the 1960s, a Houston company known as "Petro-Tex" patented a process to produce butadiene from normal butenes by oxidative dehydrogenation using a proprietary catalyst.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] It is unclear if this technology is practiced commercially.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] After World War II, the production from butenes became the major type of production in USSR.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] 1,3-Butadiene is inconvenient for laboratory use because it is gas.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Laboratory procedures have been optimized for its generation from nongaseous precursors.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] It can be produced by the retro-Diels-Alder reaction of cyclohexene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Sulfolene is a convenient solid storable source for 1,3-butadiene in the laboratory.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] It releases the diene and sulfur dioxide upon heating.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Most butadiene (75% of the manufactured 1,3-butadiene) is used to make synthetic rubbers for the manufacture of tires and components of many consumer items.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] The conversion of butadiene to synthetic rubbers is called polymerization, a process by which small molecules (monomers) are linked to make large ones (polymers).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] The mere polymerization of butadiene gives polybutadiene, which is a very soft, almost liquid material.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] The polymerization of butadiene *and* other monomers gives copolymers, which are more valued.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] The polymerization of butadiene and styrene and/or acrylonitrile, such as acrylonitrile butadiene styrene (ABS), nitrile-butadiene (NBR), styrene-butadiene (SBR) and polybutadiene acrylonitrile (PBAN).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] These copolymers are tough and/or elastic depending on the ratio of the monomers used in their preparation.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] SBR is the material most commonly used for the production of automobile tires.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Precursors to still other synthetic rubbers are prepared from butadiene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Butadiene-based polymers, particularly polybutadiene acrylonitrile (PBAN) and hydroxyl-terminated polybutadiene (HTPB) are used as binders for ammonium perchlorate composite propellant (APCP) solid rocket motors.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Large American solid rocket motors such as those used on Titan III, Space Shuttle and Space Launch System have used PBAN, while some other nations (such as Japan in M-5 rocket and India in PSLV) use HTPB.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Amateur rocketeers often use HTPB for its reduced curing temperature and fumes, despite much higher cost.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Smaller amounts of butadiene are used to make adiponitrile, a precursor to some nylons.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] The conversion of butadiene to adiponitrile entails the addition of hydrogen cyanide to each of the double bonds in butadiene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Butadiene is used to make the solvent sulfolane.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Butadiene is also useful in the synthesis of cycloalkanes and cycloalkenes, as it reacts with double and triple carbon-carbon bonds through Diels-Alder reactions.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] The most widely used such reactions involve reactions of butadiene with one or two other molecules of butadiene, i.e., dimerization and trimerization respectively.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Via dimerization butadiene is converted to 4-vinylcyclohexene and cyclooctadiene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] In fact, vinylcyclohexene is a common impurity that accumulates when butadiene is stored.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Via trimerization, butadiene is converted to cyclododecatriene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Some of these processes employ nickel- or titanium-containing catalysts.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Butadiene is also a precursor to 1-octene via palladium-catalyzed telomerization with methanol.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] This reaction produces 1-methoxy-2,7-octadiene as an intermediate.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] The most stable conformer of 1,3-butadiene is the *s*-*trans* conformation, in which the molecule is planar, with the two pairs of double bonds facing opposite directions.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] This conformation is most stable because orbital overlap between double bonds is maximized, allowing for maximum conjugation, while steric effects are minimized.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Conventionally, the *s-trans* conformation is considered to have a C2-C3 dihedral angle of 180°.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] In contrast, the *s*-*cis* conformation, in which the dihedral angle is 0°, with the pair of double bonds facing the same direction is approximately 16.5 kJ/mol (3.9 kcal/mol) higher in energy, due to steric hindrance.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] This geometry is a local energy maximum, so in contrast to the *s-trans* geometry, it is not a conformer.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] The *gauche* geometry, in which the double bonds of the *s-cis* geometry are twisted to give a dihedral angle of around 38°, is a second conformer that is around 12.0 kJ/mol (2.9 kcal/mol) higher in energy than the *s-trans* conformer.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Overall, there is a barrier of 24.8 kJ/mol (5.9 kcal/mol) for isomerization between the two conformers.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] This increased rotational barrier and strong overall preference for a near-planar geometry is evidence for a delocalized π system and a small degree of partial double bond character in the C–C single bond, in accord with resonance theory.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Despite the high energy of the *s-cis* conformation, 1,3-butadiene needs to assume this conformation (or one very similar) before it can participate as the four-electron component in concerted cycloaddition reactions like the Diels-Alder reaction.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Similarly, a combined experimental and computational study has found that the double bond of *s-trans-*butadiene has a length of 133.8 pm, while that for ethylene has a length of 133.0 pm.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] This was taken as evidence of a π-bond weakened and lengthened by delocalization, as depicted by the resonance structures shown below.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] A qualitative picture of the molecular orbitals of 1,3-butadiene is readily obtained by applying Hückel theory.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] 1,3-Butadiene is also thermodynamically stabilized.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] While a monosubstituted double bond releases about 30.3 kcal/mol of heat upon hydrogenation, 1,3-butadiene releases slightly less (57.1 kcal/mol) than twice this energy (60.6 kcal/mol), expected for two isolated double bonds.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] That implies a stabilization energy of 3.5 kcal/mol.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Similarly, the hydrogenation of the terminal double bond of 1,4-pentadiene releases 30.1 kcal/mol of heat, while hydrogenation of the terminal double bond of conjugated (*E*)-1,3-pentadiene releases only 26.5 kcal/mol, implying a very similar value of 3.6 kcal/mol for the stabilization energy.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] The ~3.5 kcal/mol difference in these heats of hydrogenation can be taken to be the resonance energy of a conjugated diene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] The industrial uses illustrate the tendency of butadiene to polymerize.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Its susceptibility to 1,4-addition reactions is illustrated by its hydrocyanation.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Like many dienes, it undergoes Pd-catalyzed reactions that proceed via allyl complexes.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] It is a partner in Diels–Alder reactions, e.g. with maleic anhydride to give tetrahydrophthalic anhydride.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Like other dienes, butadiene is a ligand for low-valent metal complexes, e.g. the derivatives Fe(butadiene)(CO)3 and Mo(butadiene)3.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] LC50 is 12.5–11.5 vol% for inhalation by rats and mice.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Long-term exposure has been associated with cardiovascular disease.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] There is a consistent association with leukemia, as well as a significant association with other cancers.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] IARC has designated 1,3-butadiene as a Group 1 carcinogen ('carcinogenic to humans'), and the Agency for Toxic Substances Disease Registry and the US EPA also list the chemical as a carcinogen.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] The American Conference of Governmental Industrial Hygienists (ACGIH) lists the chemical as a suspected carcinogen.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] The Natural Resources Defense Council (NRDC) lists some disease clusters that are suspected to be associated with this chemical.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] 1,3-Butadiene is also a suspected human teratogen.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Prolonged and excessive exposure can affect many areas in the human body; blood, brain, eye, heart, kidney, lung, nose and throat have all been shown to react to the presence of excessive 1,3-butadiene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] Animal data suggest that women have a higher sensitivity to possible carcinogenic effects of butadiene over men when exposed to the chemical.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] This may be due to estrogen receptor impacts.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] While these data reveal important implications to the risks of human exposure to butadiene, more data are necessary to draw conclusive risk assessments.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] There is also a lack of human data for the effects of butadiene on reproductive and development shown to occur in mice, but animal studies have shown breathing butadiene during pregnancy can increase the number of birth defects, and humans have the same hormone systems as animals.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/butadiene] 1,3-Butadiene is recognized as a highly reactive volatile organic compound (HRVOC) for its potential to readily form ozone, and as such, emissions of the chemical are highly regulated by TCEQ in parts of the Houston-Brazoria-Galveston Ozone Non-Attainment Area.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Coulson's major scientific work was as a pioneer of the application of the quantum theory of valency to problems of molecular structure, dynamics and reactivity.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] He was also a Methodist lay preacher, served on the World Council of Churches from 1962 to 1968, and was chairman of Oxfam from 1965 to 1971.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] The parents of Charles Coulson and his younger twin brother John Metcalfe Coulson were educators who hailed from the Midlands.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] The twins were born when their father, Alfred, was principal of Dudley Technical College and superintendent of the Methodist Sunday School, and their mother Annie Sincere Hancock was Headmistress of Tipton Elementary School, close by.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Coulson's parents maintained a religious Methodist home.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] When the Coulson brothers were 10, their father was appointed superintendent of technical colleges for the South-West of England, and the family moved to Bristol.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] When Charles was 13 he was awarded a scholarship to Clifton College in Bristol, which placed a strong emphasis on science and mathematics.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Coulson's academic success at Clifton earned him an entrance scholarship in mathematics to Trinity College, Cambridge in 1928.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] His brother John also excelled at school, and went on to become professor of chemical engineering at Newcastle University, and author of a major series of texts on chemical engineering.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] At Cambridge, Coulson first studied the Mathematics Tripos.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] He was awarded a College Senior Scholarship during his studies, and received a First Class in the university examinations in 1931.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] He continued to take the Physics Part II examination a year later, receiving another First.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] He was awarded several college and university prizes during his undergraduate days.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Ramsey and Ebenezer Cunningham were amongst his teachers.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] In 1932, Coulson started graduate work with R.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Fowler but switched to Sir John Lennard-Jones, and was awarded a Ph.D. in 1936 for work on the electronic structure of methane.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] By this time, he had published 11 papers.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] He continued as a research fellow at Cambridge for another two years.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Coulson was accredited as a lay preacher in 1929, but he said his religion was perfunctory until a particular event in 1930, which he described in a documented sermon that he gave the following year.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] His religious beliefs were influenced by the physicist Sir Arthur Eddington, the theologian Charles Raven and, in particular, by Alex(ander) Wood, Fellow of Emmanuel College, authority on acoustics and pacifist, and Labour parliamentary candidate.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] On the social side, Eileen Florence Burrett was studying in Cambridge to become a school teacher when Charles was an undergraduate.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] They came together in meetings of the University Methodists.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] They married in 1938, and had four children, two boys and two girls.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] In 1939, Coulson was appointed as senior lecturer in mathematics at University College, Dundee.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Administratively, this was still part of the University of St.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Coulson was a conscientious objector during World War II.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] He carried a very heavy work load, teaching mathematics, physics and chemistry.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Copson was head of department, on the main St.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Duncanson at University College, London, brought George Stanley Rushbrooke from Cambridge and acted technically as his Ph.D. supervisor, and wrote the first edition of *Waves*.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] In 1941 he was elected a Fellow of the Royal Society of Edinburgh, and in 1950 as a Fellow of the Royal Society of London.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] In 1945, Coulson became a lecturer in physical chemistry at Oxford University, attached to University College and, concurrently, held a Fellowship awarded by Imperial Chemical Industries.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] In 1947, Coulson accepted a university chair in theoretical physics at King's College, London.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] A news item in *Nature* described him as "among the foremost workers in Great Britain on the wave-mechanical side of quantum theory".
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Initially, Coulson's group were assigned offices on the top floor of a building (reached by a rickety wooden staircase) that overlooked the Strand, with considerable benefit when cavalcades paraded by on Lord Mayor's Day and Royal occasions.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] In 1952, the group moved down to offices in the new Physics Department, interspersed with Biophysics and other experimental groups.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] With developments in computing opening new vistas for the theoreticians, along with the developments in laboratory methods, the entire department enjoyed the intellectual ferment of the 1950s.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Percy, (3) students working for an M.Sc. on topics in applied mathematics to be followed by a Ph.D. with another supervisor in the Mathematics Department, and (4) visitors, some of whom held senior academic and industrial appointments.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] The valence theory Ph.D. students included Simon J.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Altmann, Michael P Barnett, Aagje Bozeman, Peter J.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Greenwood, Peter Higgs, Julianne Jacobs, Roland Lefebvre, George Lester, John Maddox, Norman H.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Statistical mechanics was pursued by Geoffrey V.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Chester, John Enderby, Alec Gaines and Alan B.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] The students who went on to the Mathematics Department included Godfrey Lance, Eric Milner and Geoffrey Sewell.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Collectively, these wrote nearly 30 books in later years.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Visitors who stayed for months included Professor Inga Fischer-Hjalmars of the University of Stockholm, Dr.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] John van der Waals of Shell Oil, and Dr.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Joop der Heer from the University of Amsterdam.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] In 1952, Coulson was appointed Rouse Ball Professor of Mathematics and Fellow of Wadham College at the University of Oxford.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Milne, the mathematician and astrophysicist, and Roger Penrose succeeded Coulson.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Coulson was active in the formation of the Mathematical Institute, and soon became its director.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] In 1972, Coulson was appointed to the newly created chair of theoretical chemistry.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] *Valence*, first published in 1952, and also reissued posthumously, was the most influential.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Coulson was a founder member of the board of the journal *Molecular Physics* and its first editor.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Beside his scientific works, Coulson was a committed Christian, and served as a Methodist local preacher.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] He wrote *Science, Technology and the Christian* (1953) and *Science and Christian Belief* (1955), integrating his scientific and religious views.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Coulson apparently coined the phrase God of the gaps.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Coulson believed religious faith was essential for the responsible use of science.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] He was a pacifist and conscientious objector, but championed the development of nuclear energy.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] He encouraged scientists to help improve Third World food production.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] He was chairman of Oxfam from 1965 to 1971.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] Charles' widest religious impact on the general public was in his BBC broadcasts.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] In these, and in general interaction with people, he conveyed his religiosity in a gentle and sometimes humorous manner, for example, when he claimed in his inaugural lecture at King's College, that he had received mail addressed to him as professor of theological physics.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] After a period of declining health, Coulson died in his sleep in the early hours of 7 January 1974.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/charles-coulson] He was 63 and had lived in Oxford at the time.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] These are limited to a single typographic line of symbols, which may include subscripts and superscripts.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] A chemical formula is not a chemical name since it does not contain any words.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Although a chemical formula may imply certain simple chemical structures, it is not the same as a full chemical structural formula.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Chemical formulae can fully specify the structure of only the simplest of molecules and chemical substances, and are generally more limited in power than chemical names and structural formulae.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] The simplest types of chemical formulae are called *empirical formulae*, which use letters and numbers indicating the numerical *proportions* of atoms of each type.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] **Molecular formulae** indicate the simple numbers of each type of atom in a molecule, with no information on structure.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] For example, the empirical formula for glucose is CH2O (twice as many hydrogen atoms as carbon and oxygen), while its molecular formula is C6H12O6 (12 hydrogen atoms, six carbon and oxygen atoms).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] This is possible if the relevant bonding is easy to show in one dimension.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] An example is the condensed molecular/chemical formula for ethanol, which is CH3−CH2−OH or CH3CH2OH.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] However, even a condensed chemical formula is necessarily limited in its ability to show complex bonding relationships between atoms, especially atoms that have bonds to four or more different substituents.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] For reasons of structural complexity, a single condensed chemical formula (or semi-structural formula) may correspond to different molecules, known as isomers.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] For example, glucose shares its molecular formula C6H12O6 with a number of other sugars, including fructose, galactose and mannose.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Linear equivalent chemical *names* exist that can and do specify uniquely any complex structural formula (see chemical nomenclature), but such names must use many terms (words), rather than the simple element symbols, numbers, and simple typographical symbols that define a chemical formula.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Chemical formulae may be used in chemical equations to describe chemical reactions and other chemical transformations, such as the dissolving of ionic compounds into solution.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] A chemical formula identifies each constituent element by its chemical symbol and indicates the proportionate number of atoms of each element.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] In empirical formulae, these proportions begin with a key element and then assign numbers of atoms of the other elements in the compound, by ratios to the key element.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] For molecular compounds, these ratio numbers can all be expressed as whole numbers.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] For example, the empirical formula of ethanol may be written C2H6O because the molecules of ethanol all contain two carbon atoms, six hydrogen atoms, and one oxygen atom.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Some types of ionic compounds, however, cannot be written with entirely whole-number empirical formulae.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] An example is boron carbide, whose formula of CB*n* is a variable non-whole number ratio with n ranging from over 4 to more than 6.5.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] When the chemical compound of the formula consists of simple molecules, chemical formulae often employ ways to suggest the structure of the molecule.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] These types of formulae are variously known as *molecular formulae* and *condensed formulae*.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] A molecular formula enumerates the number of atoms to reflect those in the molecule, so that the molecular formula for glucose is C6H12O6 rather than the glucose empirical formula, which is CH2O.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] However, except for very simple substances, molecular chemical formulae lack needed structural information, and are ambiguous.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] For simple molecules, a condensed (or semi-structural) formula is a type of chemical formula that may fully imply a correct structural formula.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] For example, ethanol may be represented by the condensed chemical formula CH3CH2OH, and dimethyl ether by the condensed formula CH3OCH3.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] These two molecules have the same empirical and molecular formulae (C2H6O), but may be differentiated by the condensed formulae shown, which are sufficient to represent the full structure of these simple organic compounds.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Condensed chemical formulae may also be used to represent ionic compounds that do not exist as discrete molecules, but nonetheless do contain covalently bound clusters within them.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] These polyatomic ions are groups of atoms that are covalently bound together and have an overall ionic charge, such as the sulfate [SO4]2− ion.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Each polyatomic ion in a compound is written individually in order to illustrate the separate groupings.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] For example, the compound dichlorine hexoxide has an empirical formula ClO3, and molecular formula Cl2O6, but in liquid or solid forms, this compound is more correctly shown by an ionic condensed formula [ClO2]+[ClO4]−, which illustrates that this compound consists of [ClO2]+ ions and [ClO4]− ions.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] In such cases, the condensed formula only need be complex enough to show at least one of each ionic species.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Chemical formulae as described here are distinct from the far more complex chemical systematic names that are used in various systems of chemical nomenclature.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] This name, interpreted by the rules behind it, fully specifies glucose's structural formula, but the name is not a chemical formula as usually understood, and uses terms and words not used in chemical formulae.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Such names, unlike basic formulae, may be able to represent full structural formulae without graphs.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] In chemistry, the empirical formula of a chemical is a simple expression of the relative number of each type of atom or ratio of the elements in the compound.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Empirical formulae are the standard for ionic compounds, such as CaCl2, and for macromolecules, such as SiO2.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] An empirical formula makes no reference to isomerism, structure, or absolute number of atoms.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] The term *empirical* refers to the process of elemental analysis, a technique of analytical chemistry used to determine the relative percent composition of a pure chemical substance by element.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] For example, hexane has a molecular formula of C6H14, and (for one of its isomers, n-hexane) a structural formula CH3CH2CH2CH2CH2CH3, implying that it has a chain structure of 6 carbon atoms, and 14 hydrogen atoms.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] However, the empirical formula for hexane is C3H7.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Likewise the empirical formula for hydrogen peroxide, H2O2, is simply HO, expressing the 1:1 ratio of component elements.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Formaldehyde and acetic acid have the same empirical formula, CH2O.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] This is also the molecular formula for formaldehyde, but acetic acid has double the number of atoms.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Like the other formula types detailed below, an empirical formula shows the number of elements in a molecule, and determines whether it is a binary compound, ternary compound, quaternary compound, or has even more elements.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Molecular formulae simply indicate the numbers of each type of atom in a molecule of a molecular substance.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] They are the same as empirical formulae for molecules that only have one atom of a particular type, but otherwise may have larger numbers.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] An example of the difference is the empirical formula for glucose, which is CH2O (*ratio* 1:2:1), while its molecular formula is C6H12O6 (*number of atoms* 6:12:6).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] A molecular formula provides more information about a molecule than its empirical formula, but is more difficult to establish.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] In addition to indicating the number of atoms of each elementa molecule, a structural formula indicates how the atoms are organized, and shows (or implies) the chemical bonds between the atoms.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] There are multiple types of structural formulas focused on different aspects of the molecular structure.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] The two diagrams show two molecules which are structural isomers of each other, since they both have the same molecular formula C4H10, but they have different structural formulas as shown.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] The connectivity of a molecule often has a strong influence on its physical and chemical properties and behavior.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Two molecules composed of the same numbers of the same types of atoms (i.e. a pair of isomers) might have completely different chemical and/or physical properties if the atoms are connected differently or in different positions.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] In such cases, a structural formula is useful, as it illustrates which atoms are bonded to which other ones.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] From the connectivity, it is often possible to deduce the approximate shape of the molecule.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] A condensed (or semi-structural) formula may represent the types and spatial arrangement of bonds in a simple chemical substance, though it does not necessarily specify isomers or complex structures.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] For example, ethane consists of two carbon atoms single-bonded to each other, with each carbon atom having three hydrogen atoms bonded to it.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Its chemical formula can be rendered as CH3CH3.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] In ethylene there is a double bond between the carbon atoms (and thus each carbon only has two hydrogens), therefore the chemical formula may be written: CH2CH2, and the fact that there is a double bond between the carbons is implicit because carbon has a valence of four.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] However, a more explicit method is to write H2C=CH2 or less commonly H2C::CH2.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] The two lines (or two pairs of dots) indicate that a double bond connects the atoms on either side of them.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] A triple bond may be expressed with three lines (HC≡CH) or three pairs of dots (HC:::CH), and if there may be ambiguity, a single line or pair of dots may be used to indicate a single bond.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Molecules with multiple functional groups that are the same may be expressed by enclosing the repeated group in round brackets.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] For example, isobutane may be written (CH3)3CH.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] This condensed structural formula implies a different connectivity from other molecules that can be formed using the same atoms in the same proportions (isomers).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] The formula (CH3)3CH implies a central carbon atom connected to one hydrogen atom and three methyl groups (CH3).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] The same number of atoms of each element (10 hydrogens and 4 carbons, or C4H10) may be used to make a straight chain molecule, *n*-butane: CH3CH2CH2CH3.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] The International Union of Crystallography (IUCr) has proposed a crystal-chemical formula notation that extends standard formulae with optional annotations for these items.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] The alkene called but-2-ene has two isomers, which the chemical formula CH3CH=CHCH3 does not identify.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] The relative position of the two methyl groups must be indicated by additional notation denoting whether the methyl groups are on the same side of the double bond (*cis* or *Z*) or on the opposite sides from each other (*trans* or *E*).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] As noted above, in order to represent the full structural formulae of many complex organic and inorganic compounds, chemical nomenclature may be needed which goes well beyond the available resources used above in simple condensed formulae.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] See IUPAC nomenclature of organic chemistry and IUPAC nomenclature of inorganic chemistry 2005 for examples.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] In addition, linear naming systems such as International Chemical Identifier (InChI) allow a computer to construct a structural formula, and simplified molecular-input line-entry system (SMILES) allows a more human-readable ASCII input.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] However, all these nomenclature systems go beyond the standards of chemical formulae, and technically are chemical naming systems, not formula systems.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] For polymers in condensed chemical formulae, parentheses are placed around the repeating unit.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] For example, a hydrocarbon molecule that is described as CH3(CH2)50CH3, is a molecule with fifty repeating units.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] If the number of repeating units is unknown or variable, the letter *n* may be used to indicate this formula: CH3(CH2)*n*CH3.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] For ions, the charge on a particular atom may be denoted with a right-hand superscript.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] The total charge on a charged molecule or a polyatomic ion may also be shown in this way, such as for hydronium, H3O+, or sulfate, SO2−4.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Here + and − are used in place of +1 and −1, respectively.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] For more complex ions, brackets [ ] are often used to enclose the ionic formula, as in [B12H12]2−, which is found in compounds such as caesium dodecaborate, Cs2[B12H12].
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Parentheses ( ) can be nested inside brackets to indicate a repeating unit, as in Hexamminecobalt(III) chloride, [Co(NH3)6]3+Cl−3.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Here, (NH3)6 indicates that the ion contains six ammine groups (NH3) bonded to cobalt, and [ ] encloses the entire formula of the ion with charge +3.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] This is strictly optional; a chemical formula is valid with or without ionization information, and Hexamminecobalt(III) chloride may be written as [Co(NH3)6]3+Cl−3 or [Co(NH3)6]Cl3.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Brackets, like parentheses, behave in chemistry as they do in mathematics, grouping terms together – they are not specifically employed only for ionization states.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] In the latter case here, the parentheses indicate 6 groups all of the same shape, bonded to another group of size 1 (the cobalt atom), and then the entire bundle, as a group, is bonded to 3 chlorine atoms.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] In the former case, it is clearer that the bond connecting the chlorines is ionic, rather than covalent.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Although isotopes are more relevant to nuclear chemistry or stable isotope chemistry than to conventional chemistry, different isotopes may be indicated with a prefixed superscript in a chemical formula.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] For example, the phosphate ion containing radioactive phosphorus-32 is [32PO4]3−.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Also a study involving stable isotope ratios might include the molecule 18O16O.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] A left-hand subscript is sometimes used redundantly to indicate the atomic number.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] For example, 8O2 for dioxygen, and 16 8O 2 for the most abundant isotopic species of dioxygen.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] This is convenient when writing equations for nuclear reactions, in order to show the balance of charge more clearly.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] The @ symbol (at sign) indicates an atom or molecule trapped inside a cage but not chemically bound to it.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] For example, a buckminsterfullerene (C60) with an atom (M) would simply be represented as MC60 regardless of whether M was inside the fullerene without chemical bonding or outside, bound to one of the carbon atoms.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Using the @ symbol, this would be denoted M@C60 if M was inside the carbon network.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] A non-fullerene example is [As@Ni12As20]3−, an ion in which one arsenic (As) atom is trapped in a cage formed by the other 32 atoms.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] This notation was proposed in 1991 with the discovery of fullerene cages (endohedral fullerenes), which can trap atoms such as La to form, for example, La@C60 or La@C82.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] The choice of the symbol has been explained by the authors as being concise, readily printed and transmitted electronically (the at sign is included in ASCII, which most modern character encoding schemes are based on), and the visual aspects suggesting the structure of an endohedral fullerene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Chemical formulae most often use integers for each element.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] However, there is a class of compounds, called non-stoichiometric compounds, that cannot be represented by small integers.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Such a formula might be written using decimal fractions, as in Fe0.95O, or it might include a variable part represented by a letter, as in Fe1−*x*O, where *x* is normally much less than 1.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] A chemical formula used for a series of compounds that differ from each other by a constant unit is called a *general formula*.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] It generates a homologous series of chemical formulae.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] For example, alcohols may be represented by the formula C*n*H2*n* + 1OH (*n* ≥ 1), giving the homologs methanol, ethanol, propanol for 1 ≤ *n* ≤ 3.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] When the formula contains no carbon, all the elements, including hydrogen, are listed alphabetically.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] The Hill system was first published by Edwin A.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] Hill of the United States Patent and Trademark Office in 1900.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] It is the most commonly used system in chemical databases and printed indexes to sort lists of compounds.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chemical-formula] A list of formulae in Hill system order is arranged alphabetically, as above, with single-letter elements coming before two-letter symbols when the symbols begin with the same letter (so "B" comes before "Be", which comes before "Br").
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] In modern valence bond (VB) theory calculations, **Chirgwin–Coulson weights** (also called Mulliken weights) are the relative weights of a set of possible VB structures of a molecule.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] Related methods of finding the relative weights of valence bond structures are the Löwdin and the inverse weights.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] Chirgwin and Charles Coulson who developed it in 1950.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] In valence bond theory, however, the generated structures are not necessarily orthogonal with each other, and oftentimes have substantial overlap between the two structures.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] As such, when considering non-orthogonal constituent orbitals (i.e. orbitals with non-zero overlap) the non-diagonal terms in the overlap matrix would be non-zero, and must be included in determining the weight of a constituent orbital.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] Application of the Chirgwin–Coulson formula to a molecular orbital yields the Mulliken population of the molecular orbital.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] A method of creating a linearly independent, complete set of valence bond structures for a molecule was proposed by Yuri Rumer.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] For a system with n electrons and n orbitals, Rumer's method involves arranging the orbitals in a circle and connecting the orbitals together with lines that do not intersect one another.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] Covalent, or uncharged, structures can be created by connecting all of the orbitals with one another.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] Ionic, or charged, structures for a given atom can be determined by assigning a charge to a molecule, and then following Rumer's method.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] For the case of butadiene, the 20 possible Rumer structures are shown, where 1 and 2 are the covalent structures, 3-14 are the monoionic structures, and 15-20 are the diionic structures.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] The resulting VB structures can be represented by a linear combination of determinants $|a{\overline {b}}c{\overline {d}}|$ , where a letter without an over-line indicates an electron with $\alpha$ spin, while a letter with over-line indicates an electron with $\beta$ spin.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] Where $\alpha (k)$ and $\beta (k)$ represent an $\alpha$ or $\beta$ spin on the $k^{\text{th}}$ electron, respectively.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] Where S is the overlap matrix satisfying $\langle \Phi _{i}|\Phi _{j}\rangle =S_{ij}$ .
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] The use of Löwdin and inverse weights is appropriate when the Chirgwin–Coulson weights either exceed 1 or are negative.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] Given a set of molecular orbitals, $\Psi _{1},\Psi _{2},\dots ,\Psi _{m}$ , for a molecule, consider the determinant of a given orbital population, represented by $D_{\text{MO}}$ .
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] Computing the determinant explicitly by multiplying this expression can be a computationally difficult task, given that each molecular orbital is composed of a combination of atomic orbitals.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] Note that any given molecular orbital $\Psi _{\text{MO}}$ can be written as a linear combination of atomic orbitals $\phi _{1},\phi _{2},\dots ,\phi _{n}$ , that is for each $\Psi _{i}$ , there exist $C_{ij}$ such that $\Psi _{i}=\sum \limits _{j}C_{ij}\phi _{j}$ .
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] As such, the half determinant $h_{\text{MO}}^{\alpha }$ can be further decomposed into the half determinants for an ordering of atomic orbitals $h_{r}^{\alpha }=|\phi _{1},\phi _{2},\dots ,\phi _{n}|$ corresponding to a VB structure r .
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] As such, the molecular orbital $\Psi _{i}$ can be represented as a combination of the half determinants of the atomic orbitals, $h_{\text{MO}}^{\alpha }=\sum \limits _{r}C_{r}^{\alpha }h_{r}^{\alpha }$ .
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] The same method can be used to evaluate the half determinant for the $\beta$ electrons, $h_{\text{MO}}^{\beta }$ .
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] As such, the determinant $D_{\text{MO}}$ can be expressed as $D_{\text{MO}}=\sum \limits _{r,s}C_{r}^{\alpha }C_{r}^{\beta }h_{r}^{\alpha }h_{s}^{\beta }$ , where $r,s$ index across all possible VB structures.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] The hydrogen molecule can be considered to be a linear combination of two ${\ce {H}}$ $1s$ orbitals, indicated as $\varphi _{1}$ and $\varphi _{2}$ .
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] Because structures 1 and 2 both represent covalent bonding in the hydrogen molecule and exchanging the electrons of structure 1 yields structure 2, the two covalent structures can be combined into one wave function.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] Where the negative sign arises from the antisymmetry of electron exchange.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] As such, the wave function for the ${\ce {H_2}}$ molecule, $\Psi _{{\text{H}}_{2}}$ , can be considered to be a linear combination of the Heitler-London structure and the two ionic valence bond structures.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] The overlap matrix between the atomic orbitals between the three valence bond configurations $\Phi _{HL}$ , $|\varphi _{1}{\overline {\varphi _{1}}}|$ , and $|\varphi _{2}{\overline {\varphi _{2}}}|$ is given in the output for valence bond calculations.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] Informally, the computed weights indicate that the wave function for the ${\ce {H_2}}$ molecule has a minor contribution from an ionic species not predicted from a strictly MO model for bonding.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] Determining the relative weights of each resonance structure of ozone requires, first, the determination of the possible VB structures for ${\ce {O_3}}$ .
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] Considering only the p orbitals of oxygen, and labeling the p orbital on the $i^{\text{th}}$ oxygen $\phi _{i}$ , ${\ce {O_3}}$ has 6 possible VB structures by Rumer's method.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] Where $C_{ij}$ indicates the coefficient of $\phi _{j}$ in a molecular orbital $\pi _{i}$ .
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] The weights of the standard Lewis structures for ${\ce {O_3}}$ would be $W(\Psi _{2})$ and $W(\Psi _{3})$ .
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] The weights for the standard lewis structures would be the sum of the weights of the constituent determinants.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] This compares well with reported Chirgwin–Coulson weights of 0.226 for the standard Lewis structure of ozone in the ground state.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] This also compares favorably with reported Chirgwin–Coulson weights of 0.213 for the diradical state of ozone in the ground state.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] Borazine, (chemical formula ${\ce {B_3N_3H_6}}$ ) is a cyclic, planar compound that is isoelectronic with benzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] However, VB calculations using a double-zeta D95 basis set indicate that the predominant resonance structures are the structure with all three lone pairs on the nitrogen (labeled 1 below) and the six resonance structures with one double bond between boron and nitrogen (labeled 2 below).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] The relative weights of the two structures are 0.17 and 0.08 respectively.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] By contrast, the dominant resonance structures of benzene are the two Kekule structures, with weight 0.15, and 12 monozwitterionic structures with weight 0.03.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] The data, together, indicate that, despite the similarity in appearance and structure, the electrons on borazine are less delocalized than those on benzene.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] Disulfur dinitride is a square planar compound that contains a 6 electron conjugated $\pi$ system.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] Valence bond calculations using the Dunning's D95 full double-zeta basis set indicate that the dominant resonance structure is the singlet diradical with a long nitrogen-nitrogen bond (structure 1), with Chirgwin–Coulson weight 0.47.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] This value is substantially higher than the weight for the singlet diradical centered on the sulfurs (structure 2), which has a Chirgwin–Coulson weight of 0.06.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/chirgwin-coulson-weights] This result corresponds nicely with the general rules regarding Lewis structures, namely that formal charges ought to be minimized, and contrasts with earlier computational results indicating that 1 is the dominant structure.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] DFT has been very popular for calculations in solid-state physics since the 1970s.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] However, DFT was not considered sufficiently accurate for calculations in quantum chemistry until the 1990s, when the approximations used in the theory were greatly refined to better model the exchange and correlation interactions.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Computational costs are relatively low when compared to traditional methods, such as exchange only Hartree–Fock theory and its descendants that include electron correlation.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Since, DFT has become an important tool for methods of nuclear spectroscopy such as Mössbauer spectroscopy or perturbed angular correlation, in order to understand the origin of specific electric field gradients in crystals.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] New DFT methods have been designed to overcome this problem, by alterations to the functional or by the inclusion of additive terms.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Classical density functional theory uses a similar formalism to calculate the properties of non-uniform classical fluids.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Despite the current popularity of these alterations or of the inclusion of additional terms, they are reported to stray away from the search for the exact functional.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Further, DFT potentials obtained with adjustable parameters are no longer true DFT potentials, given that they are not functional derivatives of the exchange correlation energy with respect to the charge density.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Consequently, it is not clear if the second theorem of DFT holds in such conditions.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In the context of computational materials science, *ab initio* (from first principles) DFT calculations allow the prediction and calculation of material behavior on the basis of quantum mechanical considerations, without requiring higher-order parameters such as fundamental material properties.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In contemporary DFT techniques the electronic structure is evaluated using a potential acting on the system's electrons.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] This DFT potential is constructed as the sum of external potentials *V*ext, which is determined solely by the structure and the elemental composition of the system, and an effective potential *V*eff, which represents interelectronic interactions.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Thus, a problem for a representative supercell of a material with n electrons can be studied as a set of n one-electron Schrödinger-like equations, which are also known as Kohn–Sham equations.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Although density functional theory has its roots in the Thomas–Fermi model for the electronic structure of materials, DFT was first put on a firm theoretical footing by Walter Kohn and Pierre Hohenberg in the framework of the two **Hohenberg–Kohn theorems** (HK).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The original HK theorems held only for non-degenerate ground states in the absence of a magnetic field, although they have since been generalized to encompass these.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The first HK theorem demonstrates that the ground-state properties of a many-electron system are uniquely determined by an electron density that depends on only three spatial coordinates.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] It set down the groundwork for reducing the many-body problem of N electrons with 3*N* spatial coordinates to three spatial coordinates, through the use of functionals of the electron density.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] This theorem has since been extended to the time-dependent domain to develop time-dependent density functional theory (TDDFT), which can be used to describe excited states.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The second HK theorem defines an energy functional for the system and proves that the ground-state electron density minimizes this energy functional.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In work that later won them the Nobel prize in chemistry, the HK theorem was further developed by Walter Kohn and Lu Jeu Sham to produce Kohn–Sham DFT (KS DFT).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Within this framework, the intractable many-body problem of interacting electrons in a static external potential is reduced to a tractable problem of noninteracting electrons moving in an effective potential.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The effective potential includes the external potential and the effects of the Coulomb interactions between the electrons, e.g., the exchange and correlation interactions.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Modeling the latter two interactions becomes the difficulty within KS DFT.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The simplest approximation is the local-density approximation (LDA), which is based upon exact exchange energy for a uniform electron gas, which can be obtained from the Thomas–Fermi model, and from fits to the correlation energy for a uniform electron gas.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Non-interacting systems are relatively easy to solve, as the wavefunction can be represented as a Slater determinant of orbitals.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Further, the kinetic energy functional of such a system is known exactly.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The exchange–correlation part of the total energy functional remains unknown and must be approximated.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Another approach, less popular than KS DFT but arguably more closely related to the spirit of the original HK theorems, is orbital-free density functional theory (OFDFT), in which approximate functionals are also used for the kinetic energy of the noninteracting system.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] As usual in many-body electronic structure calculations, the nuclei of the treated molecules or clusters are seen as fixed (the Born–Oppenheimer approximation), generating a static external potential V, in which the electrons are moving.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] where, for the N-electron system, Ĥ is the Hamiltonian, E is the total energy, ${\hat {T}}$ is the kinetic energy, ${\hat {V}}$ is the potential energy from the external field due to positively charged nuclei, and Û is the electron–electron interaction energy.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The operators ${\hat {T}}$ and Û are called universal operators, as they are the same for any N-electron system, while ${\hat {V}}$ is system-dependent.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] This complicated many-particle equation is not separable into simpler single-particle equations because of the interaction term Û.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] There are many sophisticated methods for solving the many-body Schrödinger equation based on the expansion of the wavefunction in Slater determinants.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] While the simplest one is the Hartree–Fock method, more sophisticated approaches are usually categorized as post-Hartree–Fock methods.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] However, the problem with these methods is the huge computational effort, which makes it virtually impossible to apply them efficiently to larger, more complex systems.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Here DFT provides an appealing alternative, being much more versatile, as it provides a way to systematically map the many-body problem, with Û, onto a single-body problem without Û.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] This relation can be reversed, i.e., for a given ground-state density *n*0(**r**) it is possible, in principle, to calculate the corresponding ground-state wavefunction Ψ0(**r**1, …, **r***N*).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The functionals *T*[*n*] and *U*[*n*] are called universal functionals, while *V*[*n*] is called a non-universal functional, as it depends on the system under study.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] with respect to *n*(**r**), assuming one has reliable expressions for *T*[*n*] and *U*[*n*].
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] A successful minimization of the energy functional will yield the ground-state density *n*0 and thus all other ground-state observables.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The variational problems of minimizing the energy functional *E*[*n*] can be solved by applying the Lagrangian method of undetermined multipliers.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] where ${\hat {T}}$ denotes the kinetic-energy operator, and ${\hat {V}}_{\text{s}}$ is an effective potential in which the particles are moving.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] where $V(\mathbf {r} )$ is the external potential, the second term is the Hartree term describing the electron–electron Coulomb repulsion, and the last term *V*XC is the exchange–correlation potential.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Here, *V*XC includes all the many-particle interactions.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Since the Hartree term and *V*XC depend on *n*(**r**), which depends on the φi, which in turn depend on *V*s, the problem of solving the Kohn–Sham equation has to be done in a self-consistent (i.e., iterative) way.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Usually one starts with an initial guess for *n*(**r**), then calculates the corresponding *V*s and solves the Kohn–Sham equations for the φi.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] From these one calculates a new density and starts again.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] This procedure is then repeated until convergence is reached.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] A non-iterative approximate formulation called Harris functional DFT is an alternative approach to this.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] It is possible to extend the DFT idea to the case of the Green function G instead of the density n.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] It is called as Luttinger–Ward functional (or kinds of similar functionals), written as *E*[*G*].
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] However, G is determined not as its minimum, but as its extremum.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Thus we may have some theoretical and practical difficulties.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] There is no one-to-one correspondence between one-body density matrix *n*(**r**, **r**′) and the one-body potential *V*(**r**, **r**′).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] (All the eigenvalues of *n*(**r**, **r**′) are 1.) In other words, it ends up with a theory similar to the Hartree–Fock (or hybrid) theory.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The same theorems can be proven in the case of relativistic electrons, thereby providing generalization of DFT for the relativistic case.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Unlike the nonrelativistic theory, in the relativistic case it is possible to derive a few exact and explicit formulas for the relativistic density functional.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Let one consider an electron in the hydrogen-like ion obeying the relativistic Dirac equation.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] where Ψ = (Ψ(1), Ψ(2), Ψ(3), Ψ(4))T is a four-component wavefunction, and E is the associated eigenenergy.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] It is easy to see that both of the above formulae represent density functionals.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The former formula can be easily generalized for the multi-electron case.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] One may observe that both of the functionals written above do not have extremals, of course, if a reasonably wide set of functions is allowed for variation.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Nevertheless, it is possible to design a density functional with desired extremal properties out of those ones.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] where *ne* in Kronecker delta symbol of the second term denotes any extremal for the functional represented by the first term of the functional F.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The second term amounts to zero for any function that is not an extremal for the first term of functional F.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] To proceed further we'd like to find Lagrange equation for this functional.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] where *A* = *mc*2∫ *ne* d*τ*, and *B* = √*m*2*c*4 + *emc*2∫*Vne* d*τ*, and *V*(*τ*0) is a value of potential at some point, specified by support of variation function *δn*, which is supposed to be infinitesimal.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Apparently, this equation could have solution only if *A* = *B*.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Solutions of this equation represent extremals for functional F.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] It's easy to see that all real densities, that is, densities corresponding to the bound states of the system in question, are solutions of written above equation, which could be called the Kohn–Sham equation in this particular case.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Looking back onto the definition of the functional F, we clearly see that the functional produces energy of the system for appropriate density, because the first term amounts to zero for such density and the second one delivers the energy value.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The major problem with DFT is that the exact functionals for exchange and correlation are not known, except for the free-electron gas.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] However, approximations exist which permit the calculation of certain physical quantities quite accurately.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In LDA, the exchange–correlation energy is typically separated into the exchange part and the correlation part: *ε*XC = *ε*X + *ε*C.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The exchange part is called the Dirac (or sometimes Slater) exchange, which takes the form *ε*X ∝ *n*1/3.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] There are, however, many mathematical forms for the correlation part.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Highly accurate formulae for the correlation energy density *ε*C(*n*↑, *n*↓) have been constructed from quantum Monte Carlo simulations of jellium.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Although unrelated to the Monte Carlo simulation, the two variants provide comparable accuracy.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The LDA assumes that the density is the same everywhere.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Because of this, the LDA has a tendency to underestimate the exchange energy and over-estimate the correlation energy.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The errors due to the exchange and correlation parts tend to compensate each other to a certain degree.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] To correct for this tendency, it is common to expand in terms of the gradient of the density in order to account for the non-homogeneity of the true electron density.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] This allows corrections based on the changes in density away from the coordinate.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Using the latter (GGA), very good results for molecular geometries and ground-state energies have been achieved.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Potentially more accurate than the GGA functionals are the meta-GGA functionals, a natural development after the GGA (generalized gradient approximation).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Meta-GGA DFT functional in its original form includes the second derivative of the electron density (the Laplacian), whereas GGA includes only the density and its first derivative in the exchange–correlation potential.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Functionals of this type are, for example, TPSS and the Minnesota Functionals.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] These functionals include a further term in the expansion, depending on the density, the gradient of the density and the Laplacian (second derivative) of the density.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Difficulties in expressing the exchange part of the energy can be relieved by including a component of the exact exchange energy calculated from Hartree–Fock theory.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Functionals of this type are known as hybrid functionals.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The DFT formalism described above breaks down, to various degrees, in the presence of a vector potential, i.e. a magnetic field.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In such a situation, the one-to-one mapping between the ground-state electron density and wavefunction is lost.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Generalizations to include the effects of magnetic fields have led to two theories: current density functional theory (CDFT) and magnetic field density functional theory (BDFT).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In both these theories, the functional used for the exchange and correlation must be generalized to include more than just the electron density.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In current density functional theory, developed by Vignale and Rasolt, the functionals become dependent on both the electron density and the paramagnetic current density.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In magnetic field density functional theory, developed by Salsbury, Grayce and Harris, the functionals depend on the electron density and the magnetic field, and the functional form can depend on the form of the magnetic field.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In both of these theories it has been difficult to develop functionals beyond their equivalent to LDA, which are also readily implementable computationally.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In general, density functional theory finds increasingly broad application in chemistry and materials science for the interpretation and prediction of complex system behavior at an atomic scale.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Specifically, DFT computational methods are applied for synthesis-related systems and processing parameters.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In such systems, experimental studies are often encumbered by inconsistent results and non-equilibrium conditions.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Examples of contemporary DFT applications include studying the effects of dopants on phase transformation behavior in oxides, magnetic behavior in dilute magnetic semiconductor materials, and the study of magnetic and electronic behavior in ferroelectrics and dilute magnetic semiconductors.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] It has also been shown that DFT gives good results in the prediction of sensitivity of some nanostructures to environmental pollutants like sulfur dioxide or acrolein, as well as prediction of mechanical properties.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In practice, Kohn–Sham theory can be applied in several distinct ways, depending on what is being investigated.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In solid-state calculations, the local density approximations are still commonly used along with plane-wave basis sets, as an electron-gas approach is more appropriate for electrons delocalised through an infinite solid.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In molecular calculations, however, more sophisticated functionals are needed, and a huge variety of exchange–correlation functionals have been developed for chemical applications.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Some of these are inconsistent with the uniform electron-gas approximation; however, they must reduce to LDA in the electron-gas limit.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In the chemistry community, one popular functional is known as BLYP (from the name Becke for the exchange part and Lee, Yang and Parr for the correlation part).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Even more widely used is B3LYP, which is a hybrid functional in which the exchange energy, in this case from Becke's exchange functional, is combined with the exact energy from Hartree–Fock theory.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Along with the component exchange and correlation functionals, three parameters define the hybrid functional, specifying how much of the exact exchange is mixed in.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The adjustable parameters in hybrid functionals are generally fitted to a "training set" of molecules.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Although the results obtained with these functionals are usually sufficiently accurate for most applications, there is no systematic way of improving them (in contrast to some of the traditional wavefunction-based methods like configuration interaction or coupled cluster theory).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In the current DFT approach it is not possible to estimate the error of the calculations without comparing them to other methods or experiments.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Density functional theory is generally highly accurate but highly computationally-expensive.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] DFT has been used with machine learning techniques – especially graph neural networks – to create machine learning potentials.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] These graph neural networks approximate DFT, with the aim of achieving similar accuracies with much less computation, and are especially beneficial for large systems.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] They are trained using DFT-calculated properties of a known set of molecules.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The predecessor to density functional theory was the **Thomas–Fermi model**, developed independently by both Llewellyn Thomas and Enrico Fermi in 1927.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] They used a statistical model to approximate the distribution of electrons in an atom.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The mathematical basis postulated that electrons are distributed uniformly in phase space with two electrons in every $h^{3}$ of volume.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] As such, they were able to calculate the energy of an atom using this kinetic-energy functional combined with the classical expressions for the nucleus–electron and electron–electron interactions (which can both also be represented in terms of the electron density).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Although this was an important first step, the Thomas–Fermi equation's accuracy is limited because the resulting kinetic-energy functional is only approximate, and because the method does not attempt to represent the exchange energy of an atom as a conclusion of the Pauli principle.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] An exchange-energy functional was added by Paul Dirac in 1928.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] However, the Thomas–Fermi–Dirac theory remained rather inaccurate for most applications.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The largest source of error was in the representation of the kinetic energy, followed by the errors in the exchange energy, and due to the complete neglect of electron correlation.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Edward Teller (1962) showed that Thomas–Fermi theory cannot describe molecular bonding.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] This can be overcome by improving the kinetic-energy functional.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The Hohenberg–Kohn theorems relate to any system consisting of electrons moving under the influence of an external potential.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] the ground-state density uniquely determines the potential and thus all properties of the system, including the many-body wavefunction.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] , is a universal functional of the density (not depending explicitly on the external potential).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In light of the fact that the sum of the occupied energies provides the energy content of the Hamiltonian, a unique functional of the ground state charge density, the spectrum of the Hamiltonian is also a unique functional of the ground state charge density.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In other words, the energy content of the Hamiltonian reaches its absolute minimum, i.e., the ground state, when the charge density is that of the ground state.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] is then the ground-state energy of this system.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The many-electron Schrödinger equation can be very much simplified if electrons are divided in two groups: valence electrons and inner core electrons.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The electrons in the inner shells are strongly bound and do not play a significant role in the chemical binding of atoms; they also partially screen the nucleus, thus forming with the nucleus an almost inert core.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Binding properties are almost completely due to the valence electrons, especially in metals and semiconductors.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] This separation suggests that inner electrons can be ignored in a large number of cases, thereby reducing the atom to an ionic core that interacts with the valence electrons.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The use of an effective interaction, a pseudopotential, that approximates the potential felt by the valence electrons, was first proposed by Fermi in 1934 and Hellmann in 1935.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In spite of the simplification pseudo-potentials introduce in calculations, they remained forgotten until the late 1950s.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] A crucial step toward more realistic pseudo-potentials was given by William C.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Topp and John Hopfield, who suggested that the pseudo-potential should be adjusted such that they describe the valence charge density accurately.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Based on that idea, modern pseudo-potentials are obtained inverting the free-atom Schrödinger equation for a given reference electronic configuration and forcing the pseudo-wavefunctions to coincide with the true valence wavefunctions beyond a certain distance rℓ.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] where *Rl*(*r*) is the radial part of the wavefunction with angular momentum ℓ, and PP and AE denote the pseudo-wavefunction and the true (all-electron) wavefunction respectively.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The index n in the true wavefunctions denotes the valence level.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The distance rℓ beyond which the true and the pseudo-wavefunctions are equal is also dependent on ℓ.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The electrons of a system will occupy the lowest Kohn–Sham eigenstates up to a given energy level according to the Aufbau principle.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] This corresponds to the steplike Fermi–Dirac distribution at absolute zero.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] If there are several degenerate or close to degenerate eigenstates at the Fermi level, it is possible to get convergence problems, since very small perturbations may change the electron occupation.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] One way of damping these oscillations is to *smear* the electrons, i.e. allowing fractional occupancies.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] One approach of doing this is to assign a finite temperature to the electron Fermi–Dirac distribution.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Other ways is to assign a cumulative Gaussian distribution of the electrons or using a Methfessel–Paxton method.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Classical density functional theory is a classical statistical method to investigate the properties of many-body systems consisting of interacting molecules, macromolecules, nanoparticles or microparticles.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The classical non-relativistic method is correct for classical fluids with particle velocities less than the speed of light and thermal de Broglie wavelength smaller than the distance between particles.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The theory is based on the calculus of variations of a thermodynamic functional, which is a function of the spatially dependent density function of particles, thus the name.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The same name is used for quantum DFT, which is the theory to calculate the electronic structure of electrons based on spatially dependent electron density with quantum and relativistic effects.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Classical DFT is a popular and useful method to study fluid phase transitions, ordering in complex liquids, physical characteristics of interfaces and nanomaterials.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Since the 1970s it has been applied to the fields of materials science, biophysics, chemical engineering and civil engineering.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Computational costs are much lower than for molecular dynamics simulations, which provide similar data and a more detailed description but are limited to small systems and short time scales.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Classical DFT is valuable to interpret and test numerical results and to define trends although details of the precise motion of the particles are lost due to averaging over all possible particle trajectories.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] As in electronic systems, there are fundamental and numerical difficulties in using DFT to quantitatively describe the effect of intermolecular interaction on structure, correlations and thermodynamic properties.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Classical DFT addresses the difficulty of describing thermodynamic equilibrium states of many-particle systems with nonuniform density.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Classical DFT has its roots in theories such as the van der Waals theory for the equation of state and the virial expansion method for the pressure.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In order to account for correlation in the positions of particles the direct correlation function was introduced as the effective interaction between two particles in the presence of a number of surrounding particles by Leonard Ornstein and Frits Zernike in 1914.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The connection to the density pair distribution function was given by the Ornstein–Zernike equation.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The importance of correlation for thermodynamic properties was explored through density distribution functions.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The functional derivative was introduced to define the distribution functions of classical mechanical systems.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Theories were developed for simple and complex liquids using the ideal gas as a basis for the free energy and adding molecular forces as a second-order perturbation.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] A term in the gradient of the density was added to account for non-uniformity in density in the presence of external fields or surfaces.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] These theories can be considered precursors of DFT.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] To develop a formalism for the statistical thermodynamics of non-uniform fluids functional differentiation was used extensively by Percus and Lebowitz (1961), which led to the Percus–Yevick equation linking the density distribution function and the direct correlation.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Other closure relations were also proposed;the Classical-map hypernetted-chain method, the BBGKY hierarchy.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In the late 1970s classical DFT was applied to the liquid–vapor interface and the calculation of surface tension.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Other applications followed: the freezing of simple fluids, formation of the glass phase, the crystal–melt interface and dislocation in crystals, properties of polymer systems, and liquid crystal ordering.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Classical DFT was applied to colloid dispersions, which were discovered to be good models for atomic systems.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] By assuming local chemical equilibrium and using the local chemical potential of the fluid from DFT as the driving force in fluid transport equations, equilibrium DFT is extended to describe non-equilibrium phenomena and fluid dynamics on small scales.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Classical DFT allows the calculation of the equilibrium particle density and prediction of thermodynamic properties and behavior of a many-body system on the basis of model interactions between particles.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The spatially dependent density determines the local structure and composition of the material.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] It is determined as a function that optimizes the thermodynamic potential of the grand canonical ensemble.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The grand potential is evaluated as the sum of the ideal-gas term with the contribution from external fields and an excess thermodynamic free energy arising from interparticle interactions.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In the simplest approach the excess free-energy term is expanded on a system of uniform density using a functional Taylor expansion.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The excess free energy is then a sum of the contributions from *s*-body interactions with density-dependent effective potentials representing the interactions between *s* particles.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In most calculations the terms in the interactions of three or more particles are neglected (second-order DFT).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] When the structure of the system to be studied is not well approximated by a low-order perturbation expansion with a uniform phase as the zero-order term, non-perturbative free-energy functionals have also been developed.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The minimization of the grand potential functional in arbitrary local density functions for fixed chemical potential, volume and temperature provides self-consistent thermodynamic equilibrium conditions, in particular, for the local chemical potential.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The functional is not in general a convex functional of the density; solutions may not be local minima.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Limiting to low-order corrections in the local density is a well-known problem, although the results agree (reasonably) well on comparison to experiment.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] A variational principle is used to determine the equilibrium density.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] It can be shown that for constant temperature and volume the correct equilibrium density minimizes the grand potential functional $\Omega$ of the grand canonical ensemble over density functions $n(\mathbf {r} )$ .
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The Helmholtz free energy functional F is defined as $F=\Omega +\int d^{3}\mathbf {r} \,n(\mathbf {r} )\mu (\mathbf {r} )$ .
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The functional derivative in the density function determines the local chemical potential: $\mu (\mathbf {r} )=\delta F(\mathbf {r} )/\delta n(\mathbf {r} )$ .
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In classical statistical mechanics the partition function is a sum over probability for a given microstate of N classical particles as measured by the Boltzmann factor in the Hamiltonian of the system.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The Hamiltonian splits into kinetic and potential energy, which includes interactions between particles, as well as external potentials.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The partition function of the grand canonical ensemble defines the grand potential.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] A correlation function is introduced to describe the effective interaction between particles.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The *s*-body density distribution function is defined as the statistical ensemble average $\langle \dots \rangle$ of particle positions.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The radial distribution function with *s* = 2 measures the change in the density at a given point for a change of the local chemical interaction at a distant point.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In a fluid the free energy is a sum of the ideal free energy and the excess free-energy contribution $\Delta F$ from interactions between particles.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The one-body direct correlation function plays the role of an effective mean field.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The functional derivative in density of the one-body direct correlation results in the direct correlation function between two particles $c_{2}$ .
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The direct correlation function is the correlation contribution to the change of local chemical potential at a point $\mathbf {r}$ for a density change at $\mathbf {r} '$ and is related to the work of creating density changes at various positions.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In dilute gases the direct correlation function is simply the pair-wise interaction between particles (Debye–Huckel equation).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Various assumptions and approximations adapted to the system under study lead to expressions for the free energy.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Correlation functions are used to calculate the free-energy functional as an expansion on a known reference system.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] If the non-uniform fluid can be described by a density distribution that is not far from uniform density a functional Taylor expansion of the free energy in density increments leads to an expression for the thermodynamic potential using known correlation functions of the uniform system.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In the square gradient approximation a strong non-uniform density contributes a term in the gradient of the density.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In a perturbation theory approach the direct correlation function is given by the sum of the direct correlation in a known system such as hard spheres and a term in a weak interaction such as the long range London dispersion force.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] In a local density approximation the local excess free energy is calculated from the effective interactions with particles distributed at uniform density of the fluid in a cell surrounding a particle.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Other improvements have been suggested such as the weighted density approximation for a direct correlation function of a uniform system which distributes the neighboring particles with an effective weighted density calculated from a self-consistent condition on the direct correlation function.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The variational Mermin principle leads to an equation for the equilibrium density and system properties are calculated from the solution for the density.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The equation is a non-linear integro-differential equation and finding a solution is not trivial, requiring numerical methods, except for the simplest models.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Classical DFT is supported by standard software packages, and specific software is currently under development.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Assumptions can be made to propose trial functions as solutions, and the free energy is expressed in the trial functions and optimized with respect to parameters of the trial functions.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] Examples are a localized Gaussian function centered on crystal lattice points for the density in a solid, the hyperbolic function $\tanh(r)$ for interfacial density profiles.
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] The extension of classical DFT towards nonequilibrium systems is known as dynamical density functional theory (DDFT).
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] with the mobility $\Gamma$ and the free energy F .
[src:chirgwin-coulson-weights/density-functional-theory] For a system of noninteracting particles, DDFT reduces to the standard diffusion equation.
